# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: international-manufacturing-technology-show
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/association-for-manufacturing-technology] The **Association for Manufacturing Technology** (**AMT**) is a trade association based in McLean, Virginia, in the United States.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/association-for-manufacturing-technology] It was founded as the National Machine Tool Builders' Association (NMTBA) in 1902.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/association-for-manufacturing-technology] It represents and promotes the interests of American providers of manufacturing machinery and equipment.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/association-for-manufacturing-technology] As machine tools advanced, NMTBA launched the first National Machine Tool Builders’ Exposition in 1927, which would later be rebranded IMTS- International Manufacturing Technology Show.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/association-for-manufacturing-technology] The AMT’s most visible activity is its management of the International Manufacturing Technology Show (IMTS), which is held on even-numbered years at McCormick Place in Chicago, Illinois.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/association-for-manufacturing-technology] AMT also supports their membership with technology centers and representative offices in China, India, Poland, Mexico and Brazil.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/association-for-manufacturing-technology] AMT puts on a number of events throughout the year.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/association-for-manufacturing-technology] While IMTS takes place in every even year, AMT also hosts the MFG Meeting and MTForecast Conference every year.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago was incorporated as a city in 1837 near a portage between the Great Lakes and the Mississippi River watershed.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] It grew rapidly in the mid-19th century.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In 1871, the Great Chicago Fire destroyed several square miles and left more than 100,000 homeless, but Chicago's population continued to grow.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago made noted contributions to urban planning and architecture, such as the Chicago School, the development of the City Beautiful movement, and the steel-framed skyscraper.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago is an international hub for finance, culture, commerce, industry, education, technology, telecommunications, and transportation.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] It has the largest and most diverse finance derivatives market in the world, generating 20% of all volume in commodities and financial futures alone.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] O'Hare International Airport is routinely ranked among the world's top ten busiest airports by passenger traffic, and the region is also the nation's railroad hub.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The Chicago area has one of the highest gross domestic products (GDP) of any urban region in the world, ranking sixth globally, generating over $919 billion in 2024.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago's economy is diverse, with no single industry employing more than 14% of the workforce.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago is a major destination for tourism, with nearly 57 million people visiting its cultural institutions, Lake Michigan beaches, restaurants, and other tourist sites in 2025.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago's culture has made significant contributions to the visual arts, literature, film, theater, comedy (especially improvisational comedy), food, dance, and music (particularly jazz, blues, soul, hip-hop, gospel, industrial, and electronic dance music, especially house music).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago is home to the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and the Lyric Opera of Chicago, while the Art Institute of Chicago has an influential visual arts museum and art school.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The Chicago area is home to the University of Chicago, Northwestern University, and the University of Illinois Chicago, among other institutions of higher education.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] It also hosts the Barack Obama Presidential Center.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Professional sports in Chicago include all major professional leagues, including two Major League Baseball teams.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The city also hosts the Chicago Marathon, one of the World Marathon Majors.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The name *Chicago* is derived from a French rendering of the indigenous Miami–Illinois word *šikaakwa*, which was a name for a wild relative of onion and garlic known to modern botanists as *Allium tricoccum*.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The first known reference to the site of the city of Chicago as "*Checagou*" was by Robert de La Salle around 1679 in a memoir.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Henri Joutel, in his journal of 1688, noted that the eponymous wild "garlic" grew profusely in the area.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The city has had several nicknames throughout its history, such as the Windy City, Chi-Town, Second City, and City of the Big Shoulders.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In the mid-18th century, the area was inhabited by the Potawatomi, an indigenous tribe who had succeeded the Miami, Sauk and Meskwaki peoples in this region.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The first known permanent settler in Chicago was a trader, Jean Baptiste Point du Sable.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Du Sable was of African descent, perhaps born in the French colony of Saint-Domingue (Haiti), and he established the settlement in the 1780s.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] He is commonly known as the "Founder of Chicago".
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In 1795, following the victory of the new United States in the Northwest Indian War, an area that was to be part of Chicago was turned over to the U.S. for a military post by native tribes in accordance with the Treaty of Greenville.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Army constructed Fort Dearborn, which was destroyed during the War of 1812 in the Battle of Fort Dearborn by the Potawatomi before being later rebuilt.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] After the War of 1812, the Odawa, Ojibwe, and Potawatomi tribes ceded additional land to the United States in the 1816 Treaty of St.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The Potawatomi were forcibly removed from their land after the 1833 Treaty of Chicago and sent west of the Mississippi River as part of the federal policy of Indian removal.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] On August 12, 1833, the Town of Chicago was organized with a population of about 200.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Within seven years it grew to more than 6,000 people.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] On June 15, 1835, the first public land sales began with Edmund Dick Taylor as Receiver of Public Monies.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The City of Chicago was incorporated on Saturday, March 4, 1837, and for several decades was the world's fastest-growing city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] As the site of the Chicago Portage, the city became an important transportation hub between the eastern and western United States.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago's first railway, Galena and Chicago Union Railroad, and the Illinois and Michigan Canal opened in 1848.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The canal allowed steamboats and sailing ships on the Great Lakes to connect to the Mississippi River.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] A flourishing economy brought residents from rural communities and immigrants from abroad.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Manufacturing and retail and finance sectors became dominant, influencing the American economy.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The Chicago Board of Trade (established 1848) listed the first-ever standardized "exchange-traded" forward contracts, which were called futures contracts.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In the 1850s, Chicago gained national political prominence as the home of Senator Stephen Douglas, the champion of the Kansas–Nebraska Act and the "popular sovereignty" approach to the issue of the spread of slavery.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] These issues also helped propel another Illinoisan, Abraham Lincoln, to the national stage.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Lincoln was nominated in Chicago for U.S. president at the 1860 Republican National Convention, which was held in a purpose-built auditorium called the Wigwam.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] He defeated Douglas in the general election, and this set the stage for the American Civil War.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] To accommodate rapid population growth and demand for better sanitation, the city improved its infrastructure.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In February 1856, Chicago's Common Council approved Chesbrough's plan to build the United States' first comprehensive sewerage system.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The project raised much of central Chicago to a new grade with the use of jackscrews for raising buildings.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] While elevating Chicago, and at first improving the city's health, the untreated sewage and industrial waste now flowed into the Chicago River, and subsequently into Lake Michigan, polluting the city's primary freshwater source.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The city responded by tunneling two miles (3.2 km) out into Lake Michigan to newly built water cribs.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In 1900, the problem of sewage contamination was largely resolved when the city completed a major engineering feat.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] It reversed the flow of the Chicago River so that the water flowed away from Lake Michigan rather than into it.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] This project began with the construction and improvement of the Illinois and Michigan Canal, and was completed with the Chicago Sanitary and Ship Canal that connects to the Illinois River, which flows into the Mississippi River.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] On October 8, 1871, the Great Chicago Fire destroyed an area about 4 miles (6.4 km) long and 1-mile (1.6 km) wide, a large section of the city at the time.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] At least 300 people were killed and over 100,000 were left homeless from the fire.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] However, much of the city, including railroads and stockyards, survived intact, and from the ruins of the previous wooden structures arose more modern constructions of steel and stone.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] These set a precedent for worldwide construction.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] During its rebuilding period, Chicago constructed the world's first skyscraper in 1885, using steel-skeleton construction.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Labor conflicts followed the industrial boom and the rapid expansion of the labor pool during the Gilded Age, including the Haymarket affair on May 4, 1886, and in 1894 the Pullman Strike.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Anarchist and socialist groups played prominent roles in creating very large and highly organized labor actions.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Concern for social problems among Chicago's immigrant poor led Jane Addams and Ellen Gates Starr to found Hull House in 1889.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Programs that were developed there became a model for the new field of social work.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] During the 1870s and 1880s, Chicago attained national stature as the leader in the movement to improve public health.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] City laws and later, state laws that upgraded standards for the medical profession and fought urban epidemics of cholera, smallpox, and yellow fever were both passed and enforced.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] These laws became templates for public health reform in other cities and states.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The city established many large, well-landscaped municipal parks, which also included public sanitation facilities.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The chief advocate for improving public health in Chicago was John H.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Rauch established a plan for Chicago's park system in 1866.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] He created Lincoln Park by closing a cemetery filled with shallow graves, and in 1867, in response to an outbreak of cholera he helped establish a new Chicago Board of Health.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Ten years later, he became the secretary and then the president of the first Illinois State Board of Health, which carried out most of its activities in Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In the 1800s, Chicago became the nation's railroad hub, and by 1910 over 20 railroads operated passenger service out of six different downtown terminals.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In 1883, Chicago's railway managers needed a general time convention, so they developed the standardized system of North American time zones.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] This system for telling time spread throughout the continent.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The desire to join the city was driven by municipal services that the city could provide its residents.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In 1893, Chicago hosted the World's Columbian Exposition on former marshland at the present location of Jackson Park.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The Exposition drew 27.5 million visitors, and is considered the most influential world's fair in history.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The city's municipal device, a Y within a circle, was the result of a contest run by the *Chicago Tribune* in 1892, in anticipation of the Columbian Exposition.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The University of Chicago, formerly at another location, moved to the same South Side location in 1892.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The term "midway" for a fair or carnival referred originally to the Midway Plaisance, a strip of park land that still runs through the University of Chicago campus and connects the Washington and Jackson Parks.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago's flourishing economy attracted huge numbers of new immigrants from Europe and migrants from the Eastern United States.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Of the total population in 1900, more than 77% were either foreign-born or born in the United States of foreign parentage.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Germans, Irish, Poles, Swedes, and Czechs made up nearly two-thirds of the foreign-born population (by 1900, whites were 98.1% of the city's population).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] During World War I and the 1920s there was a major expansion in industry.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The availability of jobs attracted African Americans from the Southern United States.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Between 1910 and 1930, the African American population of Chicago increased dramatically, from 44,103 to 233,903.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] This Great Migration had an immense cultural impact, called the Chicago Black Renaissance, part of the New Negro Movement, in art, literature, and music.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Continuing racial tensions and violence in the city, such as the Chicago race riot of 1919, also occurred.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The ratification of the 18th amendment to the Constitution in 1919 made the production and sale (including exportation) of alcoholic beverages illegal in the United States.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] This ushered in the beginning of what is known as the gangster era, a time that roughly spans from 1919 until 1933 when Prohibition was repealed.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The 1920s saw gangsters, including Al Capone, Dion O'Banion, Bugs Moran and Tony Accardo battle law enforcement and each other on the streets of Chicago during the Prohibition era.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago was the location of the infamous St.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Valentine's Day Massacre in 1929, when Al Capone sent men to gun down members of a rival gang, North Side, led by Bugs Moran, leaving seven rival members dead.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] From 1920 to 1921, the city was affected by a series of tenant rent strikes, which led to the formation of the Chicago Tenants Protective association, passage of the Kessenger tenant laws, and of a heat ordinance that legally required flats to be kept above 68 °F during winter months by landlords.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago was the first American city to have a homosexual-rights organization.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The organization, formed in 1924, was called the Society for Human Rights.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] It produced the first American publication for homosexuals, *Friendship and Freedom*.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Police and political pressure caused the organization to disband.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The Great Depression brought unprecedented suffering to Chicago, in no small part due to the city's heavy reliance on heavy industry.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Notably, industrial areas on the south side and neighborhoods lining both branches of the Chicago River were devastated; by 1933 over 50% of industrial jobs in the city had been lost, and unemployment rates amongst blacks and Latinos in the city were over 40%.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The Republican political machine in Chicago was utterly destroyed by the economic crisis, and every mayor since 1931 has been a Democrat.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] From 1928 to 1933, the city witnessed a tax revolt, and the city was unable to meet payroll or provide relief efforts.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The fiscal crisis was resolved by 1933, and at the same time, federal relief funding began to flow into Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago was also a hotbed of labor activism, with Unemployed Councils contributing heavily in the early depression to create solidarity for the poor and demand relief; these organizations were created by socialist and communist groups.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] By 1935, the Workers Alliance of America began organizing the poor, workers, the unemployed.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In the spring of 1937 Republic Steel Works witnessed the Memorial Day massacre of 1937 in the neighborhood of East Side.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In 1933, Chicago Mayor Anton Cermak was fatally wounded in Miami, Florida, during a failed assassination attempt on President-elect Franklin D.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In 1933 and 1934, the city celebrated its centennial by hosting the Century of Progress International Exposition World's Fair.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The theme of the fair was technological innovation over the century since Chicago's founding.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] During World War II, the city of Chicago alone produced more steel than the United Kingdom every year from 1939 – 1945, and more than Nazi Germany from 1943 – 1945.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The Great Migration, which had been on pause due to the Depression, resumed at an even faster pace in the second wave, as hundreds of thousands of blacks from the South arrived in the city to work in the steel mills, railroads, and shipping yards.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] On December 2, 1942, physicist Enrico Fermi conducted the world's first controlled nuclear reaction at the University of Chicago as part of the top-secret Manhattan Project.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] This led to the creation of the atomic bomb by the United States, which it used in World War II in 1945.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Daley, a Democrat, was elected in 1955, in the era of machine politics.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In 1956, the city conducted its last major expansion when it annexed the land under O'Hare airport, including a small portion of DuPage County.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] By the 1960s, white residents in several neighborhoods left the city for the suburban areas – in many American cities, a process known as white flight – as Blacks continued to move beyond the Black Belt.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] While home loan discriminatory redlining against blacks continued, the real estate industry practiced what became known as blockbusting, completely changing the racial composition of whole neighborhoods.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Structural changes in industry, such as globalization and job outsourcing, caused heavy job losses for lower-skilled workers.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] At its peak during the 1960s, some 250,000 workers were employed in the steel industry in Chicago, but the steel crisis of the 1970s and 1980s reduced this number to just 28,000 in 2015.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In 1966, Martin Luther King Jr. and Albert Raby led the Chicago Freedom Movement, which culminated in agreements between Mayor Richard J.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Two years later, the city hosted the tumultuous 1968 Democratic National Convention, which featured physical confrontations both inside and outside the convention hall, with anti-war protesters, journalists and bystanders being beaten by police.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Major construction projects, including the Sears Tower (now known as the Willis Tower, which in 1974 became the world's tallest building), University of Illinois at Chicago, McCormick Place, and O'Hare International Airport, were undertaken during Richard J.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In 1979, Jane Byrne, the city's first female mayor, was elected.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] She was notable for temporarily moving into the crime-ridden Cabrini-Green housing project and leading Chicago's school system out of a financial crisis.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In 1983, Harold Washington became the first black mayor of Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Washington's first term in office directed attention to poor and previously neglected minority neighborhoods.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] He was re‑elected in 1987 but died of a heart attack soon after.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Washington was succeeded by 6th ward alderperson Eugene Sawyer, who was elected by the Chicago City Council and served until a special election.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] His accomplishments included improvements to parks and creating incentives for sustainable development, as well as closing Meigs Field in the middle of the night and destroying the runways.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] After successfully running for re-election five times, and becoming Chicago's longest-serving mayor, Richard M.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Daley declined to run for a seventh term.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In 1992, a construction accident near the Kinzie Street Bridge produced a breach connecting the Chicago River to a tunnel below, which was part of an abandoned freight tunnel system extending throughout the downtown Loop district.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The tunnels filled with 250 million US gallons (1,000,000 m3) of water, affecting buildings throughout the district and forcing a shutdown of electrical power.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The area was shut down for three days and some buildings did not reopen for weeks; losses were estimated at $1.95 billion.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] On February 23, 2011, Rahm Emanuel, a former White House Chief of Staff and member of the House of Representatives, won the mayoral election.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Emanuel was sworn in as mayor on May 16, 2011, and won re-election in 2015.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Lori Lightfoot, the city's first African American woman mayor and its first openly LGBTQ mayor, was elected to succeed Emanuel as mayor in 2019.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] All three city-wide elective offices were held by women (and women of color) for the first time in Chicago history: in addition to Lightfoot, the city clerk was Anna Valencia and the city treasurer was Melissa Conyears-Ervin.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] On May 15, 2023, Brandon Johnson assumed office as the 57th mayor of Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago is located in northeastern Illinois on the southwestern shores of freshwater Lake Michigan.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] It is the principal city in the Chicago Metropolitan Area, situated in both the Midwestern United States and the Great Lakes region.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The city rests on a continental divide at the site of the Chicago Portage, connecting the Mississippi River and the Great Lakes watersheds.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In addition to it lying beside Lake Michigan, two rivers—the Chicago River in downtown and the Calumet River in the industrial far South Side—flow either entirely or partially through the city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago's history and economy are closely tied to its proximity to Lake Michigan.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] While the Chicago River historically handled much of the region's waterborne cargo, today's huge lake freighters use the city's Lake Calumet Harbor on the South Side.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The lake also provides another positive effect: moderating Chicago's climate, making waterfront neighborhoods slightly warmer in winter and cooler in summer.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] When Chicago was founded in 1837, most of the early building was around the mouth of the Chicago River, as can be seen on a map of the city's original 58 blocks.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The overall grade of the city's central, built-up areas is relatively consistent with the natural flatness of its overall natural geography, generally exhibiting only slight differentiation otherwise.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The average land elevation is 579 ft (176.5 m) above sea level.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] While measurements vary somewhat, the lowest points are along the lake shore at 578 ft (176.2 m), while the highest point, at 672 ft (205 m), is the morainal ridge of Blue Island in the city's far south side.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Lake Shore Drive runs adjacent to a large portion of Chicago's waterfront.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Some of the parks along the waterfront include Lincoln Park, Grant Park, Burnham Park, and Jackson Park.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] There are 24 public beaches across 26 miles (42 km) of the waterfront.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Landfill extends into portions of the lake providing space for Navy Pier, Northerly Island, the Museum Campus, and large portions of the McCormick Place Convention Center.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Most of the city's high-rise commercial and residential buildings are close to the waterfront.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] An informal name for the entire Chicago metropolitan area is "Chicagoland", which generally means the city and all its suburbs, though different organizations have slightly different definitions.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Major sections of the city include the central business district, called the Loop, and the North, South, and West Sides.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The three sides of the city are represented on the Flag of Chicago by three horizontal white stripes.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The North Side is the city's most densely populated residential section, and many high-rises are on this side of the city along the lakefront.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The South Side is the city's largest section, encompassing roughly 60% of its land area.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The South Side contains most of the facilities of the Port of Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In the late 1920s, sociologists at the University of Chicago subdivided the city into 75 distinct community areas, plus O'Hare in 1956 and Edgewater in 1980 for a total of 77.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The community areas can further be subdivided into over 200 informally defined neighborhoods.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago's streets were laid out in a street grid that grew from the city's original townsite plot, which was bounded by Lake Michigan on the east, North Avenue on the north, Wood Street on the west, and 22nd Street on the south.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Streets following the Public Land Survey System section lines later became arterial streets in outlying sections.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] As new additions to the city were platted, city ordinance required them to be laid out with eight streets to the mile in one direction and sixteen in the other direction, about one street per 200 meters in one direction and one street per 100 meters in the other direction.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The grid's regularity provided an efficient means of developing new real estate property.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] A scattering of diagonal streets, many of them originally Native American trails, also cross the city (Elston, Milwaukee, Ogden, Lincoln, etc.).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Many additional diagonal streets were recommended in the Plan of Chicago, but only the extension of Ogden Avenue was ever constructed.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In 2021, Chicago was ranked the fourth-most walkable large city in the United States.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Many of the city's residential streets have a wide patch of grass or trees between the street and the sidewalk itself.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] This helps to keep pedestrians on the sidewalk further away from the street traffic.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago's Western Avenue is the longest continuous urban street in the world.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Other notable streets include Michigan Avenue, State Street, 95th Street, Cicero Avenue, Clark Street, and Belmont Avenue.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The City Beautiful movement inspired Chicago's boulevards and parkways.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The destruction caused by the Great Chicago Fire led to the largest building boom in the history of the nation.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In 1885, the first steel-framed high-rise building, the Home Insurance Building, rose in the city as Chicago ushered in the skyscraper era, which would then be followed by many other cities around the world.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Today, Chicago's skyline is among the world's tallest and densest.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Some of the United States' tallest towers are located in Chicago; Willis Tower (formerly Sears Tower) is the third tallest building in the Western Hemisphere after One World Trade Center, and Central Park Tower.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The Loop's historic buildings include the Chicago Board of Trade Building, the Fine Arts Building, 35 East Wacker, and the Chicago Building, 860-880 Lake Shore Drive Apartments by Mies van der Rohe.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Many other architects have left their impression on the Chicago skyline such as Daniel Burnham, Louis Sullivan, Charles B.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The Merchandise Mart, once the largest building in the world, had its own zip code until 2008, and stands near the junction of the North and South branches of the Chicago River.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Presently, the four tallest buildings in the city are Willis Tower (formerly the Sears Tower, also a building with its own zip code), Trump International Hotel and Tower, the Aon Center (previously the Standard Oil Building), and the John Hancock Center.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Industrial districts, such as some areas on the South Side, the areas along the Chicago Sanitary and Ship Canal, and the Northwest Indiana area are clustered.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago gave its name to the Chicago School and was home to the Prairie School, two movements in architecture.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Multiple kinds and scales of houses, townhouses, condominiums, and apartment buildings can be found throughout Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Large swaths of the city's residential areas away from the lake are characterized by brick bungalows built from the early 20th century through the end of World War II.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago is also a prominent center of the Polish Cathedral style of church architecture.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The Chicago suburb of Oak Park was home to famous architect Frank Lloyd Wright, who had designed The Robie House located near the University of Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] A popular tourist activity is to take an architecture boat tour along the Chicago River.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago is famous for its outdoor public art with donors establishing funding for such art as far back as Benjamin Ferguson's 1905 trust.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] A number of Chicago's public art works are by modern figurative artists.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Some events which shaped the city's history have also been memorialized by art works, including the Great Northern Migration (Saar) and the centennial of statehood for Illinois.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Finally, two fountains near the Loop also function as monumental works of art: Plensa's Crown Fountain as well as Burnham and Bennett's Buckingham Fountain.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The city mostly lies within the typical hot-summer humid continental climate (Köppen: *Dfa*), and experiences four distinct seasons.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Summers are hot and humid, with frequent heat waves.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The July daily average temperature is 75.4 °F (24.1 °C), with afternoon temperatures peaking at 84.5 °F (29.2 °C).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In a normal summer, temperatures reach at least 90 °F (32 °C) on 17 days, with lakefront locations staying cooler when winds blow off the lake.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Blizzards do occur, such as in winter 2011.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The normal winter high from December through March is about 36 °F (2 °C).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] January and February are the coldest months.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] A polar vortex in January 2019 nearly broke the city's cold record of −27 °F (−33 °C), which was set on January 20, 1985.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Measurable snowfall can continue through the first or second week of April.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Spring and autumn are mild, short seasons, typically with low humidity.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Dew point temperatures in the summer range from an average of 55.8 °F (13.2 °C) in June to 61.7 °F (16.5 °C) in July.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] They can reach nearly 80 °F (27 °C), such as during the July 2019 heat wave.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The city lies within USDA plant hardiness zone 6a, transitioning to 5b in the suburbs.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] According to the National Weather Service, Chicago's highest official temperature reading of 105 °F (41 °C) was recorded on July 24, 1934.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Midway Airport reached 109 °F (43 °C) one day prior and recorded a heat index of 125 °F (52 °C) during the 1995 heatwave.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The lowest official temperature of −27 °F (−33 °C) was recorded on January 20, 1985, at O'Hare Airport.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Most of the city's rainfall is brought by thunderstorms, averaging 38 a year.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The region is prone to severe thunderstorms during the spring and summer which can produce large hail, damaging winds, and occasionally tornadoes.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Notably, the F4 Oak Lawn tornado moved through the South Side of the city on April 21, 1967, moving onto Lake Michigan as a waterspout.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Downtown Chicago was struck by an F3 tornado on May 6, 1876, again moving out over Lake Michigan.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Like other major cities, Chicago experiences an urban heat island, making the city and its suburbs milder than surrounding rural areas, especially at night and in winter.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Northeast winds from wintertime cyclones departing south of the region sometimes bring the city lake-effect snow.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] During its first hundred years, Chicago was one of the fastest-growing cities in the world.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] When founded in 1833, fewer than 200 people had settled on what was then the American frontier.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] By the time of its first census, seven years later, the population had reached over 4,000.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In the forty years from 1850 to 1890, the city's population grew from slightly under 30,000 to over 1 million.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] By the 1890 census, Chicago was the second most populous city in the United States.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] By 1900, it was the fifth largest in the world behind Berlin, Paris, New York, and London, and the largest city founded in the prior century.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Within sixty years of the Great Chicago Fire of 1871, the population went from about 300,000 to over 3 million, and reached its highest ever recorded population of 3.6 million for the 1950 census.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] To these ethnic groups, the basis of the city's industrial working class, were added an additional influx of African Americans from the American South as part of the Great Migration—with Chicago's black population doubling between 1910 and 1920 and doubling again between 1920 and 1930.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago has a significant Bosnian population, many of whom arrived in the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In the 1920s and 1930s, the great majority of African Americans moving to Chicago settled in a so‑called "Black Belt" on the city's South Side.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] A large number of blacks also settled on the West Side.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] By 1930, two-thirds of Chicago's black population lived in sections of the city which were 90% black in racial composition.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Around that time, the block of 4600 Winthrop Avenue in the Uptown neighborhood was the only one in the neighborhood on which African Americans could live or open establishments.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago's South Side emerged as United States second-largest urban black concentration, following New York's Harlem.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In 1990, Chicago's South Side and the adjoining south suburbs constituted the largest black majority region in the entire United States.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Since the 1980s, Chicago has had a massive exodus of African Americans (primarily from the South and West sides) to its suburbs or outside its metropolitan area.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The above average crime and cost of living were leading reasons for the fast declining African American population in Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Most of Chicago's foreign-born population were born in Mexico, Poland or India.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] A 2020 study estimated the total Jewish population of the Chicago metropolitan area, both religious and irreligious, at 319,500.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago's population declined in the latter half of the 20th century, from over 3.6 million in 1950 down to under 2.7 million by 2010.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] By the time of the official census count in 1990, it was overtaken by Los Angeles as the United States' second largest city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] It then saw a rise in population for the 2000 census, a decrease in 2010, and another increase for the 2020 census.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] According to U.S. census estimates as of July 2019, Chicago's largest racial or ethnic group is non-Hispanic White at 32.8% of the population, Blacks at 30.1% and the Hispanic population at 29.0% of the population.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago became a "de jure" sanctuary city in 2012 when Mayor Rahm Emanuel and the City Council passed the Welcoming City Ordinance.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Census Bureau's American Community Survey data estimates for 2022, the median income for a household in the city was $70,386, and the per capita income was $45,449.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Male full-time workers had a median income of $68,870 versus $60,987 for females.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] About 17.2% of the population lived below the poverty line.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In 2018, Chicago ranked seventh globally for the highest number of ultra-high-net-worth residents with roughly 3,300 residents worth more than $30 million.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Persons who did not report or classify an ancestry were 548,790.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago has the third-largest lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, and queer (LGBTQ) population in the United States.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Since the 2013 legalization of same-sex marriage in Illinois, over 10,000 same-sex couples have wed in Illinois' Cook County, a majority of them in Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago is the first U.S. city to have a pro-gay organization and consistently ranks as one of the most LGBTQ-friendly cities in the nation.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Lake View and Edgewater are historically the epicenters of LGBTQ culture in Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] According to a 2014 study by the Pew Research Center, Christianity is the most prevalently practiced religion in Chicago (71%), with the city being the fourth-most religious metropolis in the United States after Dallas, Atlanta and Houston.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Roman Catholicism and Protestantism are the largest branches (34% and 35% respectively), followed by Eastern Orthodoxy and Jehovah's Witnesses with 1% each.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago also has a sizable non-Christian population.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Non-Christian groups include Irreligious (22%), Judaism (3%), Islam (2%), Buddhism (1%) and Hinduism (1%).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Chicago is the headquarters of several religious denominations, including the Evangelical Covenant Church and the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The Fourth Presbyterian Church is one of the largest Presbyterian congregations in the United States based on memberships.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Since the 20th century Chicago has also been the headquarters of the Assyrian Church of the East.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] In 2014 the Catholic Church was the largest individual Christian denomination (34%), with the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Chicago being the largest Catholic jurisdiction.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Evangelical Protestantism form the largest theological Protestant branch (16%), followed by Mainline Protestants (11%), and historically Black churches (8%).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Among denominational Protestant branches, Baptists formed the largest group in Chicago (10%); followed by Nondenominational (5%); Lutherans (4%); and Pentecostals (3%).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Non-Christian faiths accounted for 7% of the religious population in 2014.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Judaism has at least 261,000 adherents which is 3% of the population.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] The first two Parliament of the World's Religions in 1893 and 1993 were held in Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Many international religious leaders have visited Chicago, including Mother Teresa, the Dalai Lama and Pope John Paul II in 1979.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p01] Pope Leo XIV was born in Chicago in 1955 and graduated from the Catholic Theological Union in Hyde Park.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago has the third-largest gross metropolitan product in the United States—about $670.5 billion according to September 2017 estimates.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The city has also been rated as having the most balanced economy in the United States, due to its high level of diversification.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Chicago metropolitan area has the third-largest science and engineering work force of any metropolitan area in the nation.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago was the base of commercial operations for industrialists John Crerar, John Whitfield Bunn, Richard Teller Crane, Marshall Field, John Farwell, Julius Rosenwald, and many other commercial visionaries who laid the foundation for Midwestern and global industry.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago is a major world financial center, with the second-largest central business district in the United States, following Midtown Manhattan.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The city is the seat of the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago, the Bank's Seventh District.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The city has major financial and futures exchanges, including the Chicago Stock Exchange, the Cboe Global Markets Options Exchange, and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange (the "Merc"), which is owned, along with the Chicago Board of Trade (CBOT), by Chicago's CME Group.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] In 2017, Chicago exchanges traded 4.7 billion in derivatives.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chase Bank has its commercial and retail banking headquarters in Chicago's Chase Tower.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Academically, Chicago has been influential through the Chicago school of economics, which fielded 12 Nobel Prize winners.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The city and its surrounding metropolitan area contain the third-largest labor pool in the United States with about 4.63 million workers.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Illinois is home to 66 *Fortune* 1000 companies, including those in Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The city of Chicago also hosts 12 *Fortune* Global 500 companies and 17 *Financial Times* 500 companies.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The city claims three Dow 30 companies: aerospace giant Boeing, which moved its headquarters from Seattle to the Chicago Loop in 2001; McDonald's; and Walgreens Boots Alliance.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] For six consecutive years from 2013 through 2018, Chicago was ranked the nation's top metropolitan area for corporate relocations.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] However, three *Fortune* 500 companies left Chicago in 2022, leaving the city with 35, still second to New York City.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Manufacturing, printing, publishing, and food processing also play major roles in the city's economy.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Several medical products and services companies are based in the Chicago area, including Baxter International, Boeing, Abbott Laboratories, and the Healthcare division of General Electric.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Prominent food companies based in Chicago include the world headquarters of Conagra, Ferrara Candy Company, Kraft Heinz, McDonald's, Mondelez International, and Quaker Oats.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago has been a hub of the retail sector since its early development, with Montgomery Ward, Sears, and Marshall Field's.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Today the Chicago metropolitan area is the headquarters of several retailers, including Walgreens, Sears, Ace Hardware, Claire's, ULTA Beauty, and Crate & Barrel.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Tech companies based in the area include CDW, Uber Frieght, Zebra Technologies, Motorola Solutions, Motorola along with regional offices for Google, Salesforce, LinkedIn, and more.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago was also the site of the Schwinn Bicycle Company.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago is a major world convention destination.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The city's main convention center is McCormick Place.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] With its four interconnected buildings, it is the largest convention center in the nation and third-largest in the world.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] (behind Las Vegas and Orlando) in number of conventions hosted annually.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago's minimum wage for non-tipped employees is one of the highest in the nation and reached $15 in 2021.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The city's waterfront location and nightlife attracts residents and tourists alike.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Over a third of the city population is concentrated in the lakefront neighborhoods from Rogers Park in the north to South Shore in the south.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The city has many upscale dining establishments as well as many ethnic restaurant districts.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Downtown is the center of Chicago's financial, cultural, governmental, and commercial institutions and the site of Grant Park and many of the city's skyscrapers.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Many of the city's financial institutions, such as the CBOT and the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago, are located within a section of downtown called "The Loop", which is an eight-block by five-block area of city streets that is encircled by elevated rail tracks.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The term "The Loop" is largely used by locals to refer to the entire downtown area as well.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The central area includes the Near North Side, the Near South Side, and the Near West Side, as well as the Loop.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] These areas contribute famous skyscrapers, abundant restaurants, shopping, museums, Soldier Field, convention facilities, parkland, and beaches.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Lincoln Park contains Lincoln Park Zoo and Lincoln Park Conservatory.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The River North Gallery District features the nation's largest concentration of contemporary art galleries outside of New York City.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Lake View is home to Boystown, the city's large LGBT nightlife and culture center.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Chicago Pride Parade, held the last Sunday in June, is one of the world's largest with over a million people in attendance.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] North Halsted Street is the main thoroughfare of Boystown.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The South Side neighborhood of Hyde Park is the home of former U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] President Barack Obama and First Lady Michelle Obama.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The neighborhood is home to the Barack Obama Presidential Center, a museum and library dedicated to his presidency.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] It also contains the University of Chicago, ranked one of the world's top ten universities, and the Museum of Science and Industry.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The 6-mile (9.7 km) long Burnham Park stretches along the waterfront of the South Side.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Two of the city's largest parks are also located on this side of the city: Jackson Park, bordering the waterfront, hosted the World's Columbian Exposition in 1893, and is the site of the aforementioned museum; and slightly west sits Washington Park.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The two parks themselves are connected by a wide strip of parkland called the Midway Plaisance, running adjacent to the University of Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The South Side hosts one of the city's largest parades, the annual African American Bud Billiken Parade and Picnic, which travels through Bronzeville to Washington Park.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Ford Motor Company has an automobile assembly plant on the South Side in Hegewisch, and most of the facilities of the Port of Chicago are also on the South Side.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The West Side holds the Garfield Park Conservatory, one of the largest collections of tropical plants in any U.S. city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Prominent Latino cultural attractions found here include Humboldt Park's Institute of Puerto Rican Arts and Culture and the annual Puerto Rican People's Parade, as well as the National Museum of Mexican Art and St.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Near West Side holds the University of Illinois at Chicago and was once home to Oprah Winfrey's Harpo Studios, the site of which has been rebuilt as the global headquarters of McDonald's.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The city's distinctive accent, made famous by its use in classic films like *The Blues Brothers* and television programs like the *Saturday Night Live* skit "Bill Swerski's Superfans", is an advanced form of Inland Northern American English.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] This dialect can be found in other cities bordering the Great Lakes, such as Detroit, Cleveland, Milwaukee, and Buffalo, New York, and most prominently features a rearrangement of certain vowel sounds, such as the short "a" sound as in "cat", which can sound more like "kyet" to outsiders.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The accent remains well associated with the city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Renowned Chicago theater companies include the Goodman Theatre in the Loop; the Steppenwolf Theatre Company and Victory Gardens Theater in Lincoln Park; and the Chicago Shakespeare Theater at Navy Pier.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Broadway In Chicago offers Broadway-style entertainment at five theaters: the Nederlander Theatre, CIBC Theatre, Cadillac Palace Theatre, Auditorium Building of Roosevelt University, and Broadway Playhouse at Water Tower Place.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Polish language productions for Chicago's large Polish speaking population can be seen at the historic Gateway Theatre in Jefferson Park.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Since 1968, the Joseph Jefferson Awards are given annually to acknowledge excellence in theater in the Chicago area.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago's theater community spawned modern improvisational theater, and includes the prominent groups The Second City and I.O.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Chicago Symphony Orchestra (CSO) performs at Symphony Center, and is recognized as one of the best orchestras in the world.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Also performing regularly at Symphony Center is the Chicago Sinfonietta, a more diverse and multicultural counterpart to the CSO.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] In the summer, many outdoor concerts are given in Grant Park and Millennium Park.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Ravinia Festival, located 25 miles (40 km) north of Chicago, is the summer home of the CSO, and is a favorite destination for many Chicagoans.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Civic Opera House is home to the Lyric Opera of Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Lithuanian Opera Company of Chicago was founded by Lithuanian Chicagoans in 1956, and presents operas in Lithuanian.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Joffrey Ballet and Chicago Festival Ballet perform in various venues, including the Harris Theater in Millennium Park.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago has several other contemporary and jazz dance troupes, such as the Hubbard Street Dance Chicago and Chicago Dance Crash.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Other live-music genre which are part of the city's cultural heritage include Chicago blues, Chicago soul, jazz, and gospel.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The city is the birthplace of house music (a popular form of electronic dance music) and industrial music, and is the site of an influential hip hop scene.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] In the 1980s and 90s, the city was the global center for house and industrial music, two forms of music created in Chicago, as well as being popular for alternative rock, punk, and new wave.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The city has been a center for rave culture, since the 1980s.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] A flourishing independent rock music culture brought forth Chicago indie.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Annual festivals feature various acts, such as Lollapalooza and the Pitchfork Music Festival.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Lollapalooza originated in 1991 as a touring festival, but as of 2005 its home has been Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] A 2007 report on the Chicago music industry by the University of Chicago Cultural Policy Center ranked Chicago third among metropolitan U.S. areas in "size of music industry" and fourth among all U.S. cities in "number of concerts and performances".
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago has a distinctive fine art tradition.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] For much of the twentieth century, it nurtured a strong style of figurative surrealism, as in the works of Ivan Albright and Ed Paschke.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] In 1968 and 1969, members of the Chicago Imagists, such as Roger Brown, Leon Golub, Robert Lostutter, Jim Nutt, and Barbara Rossi produced bizarre representational paintings.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Henry Darger is one of the most celebrated figures of outsider art.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] In 2014, Chicago attracted 50.17 million domestic leisure travelers, 11.09 million domestic business travelers and 1.308 million overseas visitors.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] These visitors contributed more than US$13.7 billion to Chicago's economy.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Upscale shopping along the Magnificent Mile and State Street, thousands of restaurants, as well as Chicago's architecture, continue to draw tourists.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The city is the United States' third-largest convention destination.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] A 2017 study by Walk Score ranked Chicago the sixth-most walkable of fifty largest cities in the United States.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Most conventions are held at McCormick Place, just south of Soldier Field.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Navy Pier, located just east of Streeterville, is 3,000 ft (910 m) long and houses retail stores, restaurants, museums, exhibition halls and auditoriums.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Ferris wheel first appeared at the World's Columbian Exposition, held in Chicago in 1893.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Willis Tower, formerly named Sears Tower, is a popular destination for tourists.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Among the city's museums are the Adler Planetarium & Astronomy Museum, the Field Museum of Natural History, and the Shedd Aquarium.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Museum Campus joins the southern section of Grant Park, which includes the renowned Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Buckingham Fountain anchors the downtown park along the lakefront.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The University of Chicago's Institute for the Study of Ancient Cultures, West Asia & North Africa has an extensive collection of ancient Egyptian and Near Eastern archaeological artifacts.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago lays claim to a large number of regional specialties that reflect the city's ethnic and working-class roots.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Included among these are its nationally renowned deep-dish pizza; this style is said to have originated at Pizzeria Uno.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Chicago-style thin crust is also popular in the city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Certain Chicago pizza favorites include Lou Malnati's and Giordano's.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Chicago-style hot dog, typically an all-beef hot dog, is loaded with an array of toppings that often includes pickle relish, yellow mustard, pickled sport peppers, tomato wedges, dill pickle spear and topped off with celery salt on a poppy seed bun.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Enthusiasts of the Chicago-style hot dog frown upon the use of ketchup as a garnish, but may prefer to add giardiniera.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] A distinctly Chicago sandwich, the Italian beef sandwich is thinly sliced beef simmered in au jus and served on an Italian roll with sweet peppers or spicy giardiniera.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] A popular modification is the Combo—an Italian beef sandwich with the addition of an Italian sausage.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Maxwell Street Polish is a grilled or deep-fried kielbasa—on a hot dog roll, topped with grilled onions, yellow mustard, and hot sport peppers.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicken Vesuvio is roasted bone-in chicken cooked in oil and garlic next to garlicky oven-roasted potato wedges and a sprinkling of green peas.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Puerto Rican-influenced jibarito is a sandwich made with flattened, fried green plantains instead of bread.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The mother-in-law is a tamale topped with chili and served on a hot dog bun.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The tradition of serving the Greek dish saganaki while aflame has its origins in Chicago's Greek community.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The appetizer, which consists of a square of fried cheese, is doused with Metaxa and flambéed table-side.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago-style barbecue features hardwood smoked rib tips and hot links which were traditionally cooked in an aquarium smoker, a Chicago invention.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Annual festivals feature various Chicago signature dishes, such as Taste of Chicago and the Chicago Food Truck Festival.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] One of the world's most decorated restaurants and a recipient of three Michelin stars, Alinea is located in Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Well-known chefs who have had restaurants in Chicago include: Charlie Trotter, Rick Tramonto, Grant Achatz, and Rick Bayless.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] In 2003, *Robb Report* named Chicago the country's "most exceptional dining destination".
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago literature finds its roots in the city's tradition of lucid, direct journalism, lending to a strong tradition of social realism.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Narrative fiction of that time, much of it in the style of "high-flown romance" and "genteel realism", needed a new approach to describe the urban social, political, and economic conditions of Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Nonetheless, Chicagoans worked hard to create a literary tradition that would stand the test of time, and create a "city of feeling" out of concrete, steel, vast lake, and open prairie.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Much notable Chicago fiction focuses on the city itself, with social criticism keeping exultation in check.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] At least three short periods in the history of Chicago have had a lasting influence on American literature.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] These include from the time of the Great Chicago Fire to about 1900, what became known as the Chicago Literary Renaissance in the 1910s and early 1920s, and the period of the Great Depression to the 1940s.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] What would become the influential *Poetry* magazine was founded in 1912 by Harriet Monroe, who was working as an art critic for the *Chicago Tribune*.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The magazine discovered such poets as Gwendolyn Brooks, James Merrill, and John Ashbery.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Eliot's first professionally published poem, "The Love Song of J.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Alfred Prufrock", was first published by *Poetry*.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Contributors have included Ezra Pound, William Butler Yeats, William Carlos Williams, Langston Hughes, and Carl Sandburg, among others.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The magazine was instrumental in launching the Imagist and Objectivist poetic movements.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] From the 1950s to the 1970s, American poetry continued to evolve in Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] In the 1980s, a modern form of poetry performance began in Chicago, the poetry slam.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The city has two Major League Baseball (MLB) teams: the Chicago Cubs of the National League play in Wrigley Field on the North Side; and the Chicago White Sox of the American League play in Rate Field on the South Side.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The two teams have faced each other in a World Series only once, in 1906.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Cubs are the oldest Major League Baseball team to have never changed their city; they have played in Chicago since 1871.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] They had the dubious honor of having the longest championship drought in American professional sports, failing to win a World Series between 1908 and 2016.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The White Sox have played on the South Side continuously since 1901.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] They have won three World Series titles (1906, 1917, 2005) and six American League pennants, including the first in 1901.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Chicago Bears, one of the last two remaining charter members of the National Football League (NFL), have won nine NFL Championships, including the 1985 Super Bowl XX.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Bears play their home games at Soldier Field.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Chicago Bulls of the National Basketball Association (NBA) is one of the most recognized basketball teams in the world.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] During the 1990s, with Michael Jordan leading them, the Bulls won six NBA championships in eight seasons.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Chicago Blackhawks of the National Hockey League (NHL) began play in 1926, and are one of the "Original Six" teams of the NHL.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Blackhawks have won six Stanley Cups, including in 2010, 2013, and 2015.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Both the Bulls and the Blackhawks play at the United Center.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago Fire FC is a member of Major League Soccer (MLS) and plays at Soldier Field.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Fire have won one league title and four U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Open Cups, since their founding in 1997.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] In 1994, the United States hosted a successful FIFA World Cup with games played at Soldier Field.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Chicago Stars FC are a team in the National Women's Soccer League (NWSL).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] They previously played in Women's Professional Soccer (WPS), of which they were a founding member, before joining the NWSL in 2013.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] They play at SeatGeek Stadium in Bridgeview, Illinois.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Chicago Sky is a professional basketball team playing in the Women's National Basketball Association (WNBA).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] They play home games at the Wintrust Arena.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The team was founded before the 2006 WNBA season began.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Chicago Marathon has been held each year since 1977 except for 1987, when a half marathon was run in its place.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Chicago Marathon is one of six World Marathon Majors.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Chicago Street Course in downtown Chicago had races in the Cup Series and Xfinity Series from 2023 to 2025, while the often forgotten Chicago Motor Speedway held CART and NASCAR Truck Series races.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago has also entered into esports with the creation of the OpTic Chicago, a professional Call of Duty team that participates within the CDL.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] When Chicago was incorporated in 1837, it chose the motto *Urbs in Horto*, a Latin phrase which means "City in a Garden".
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Today, the Chicago Park District consists of more than 570 parks with over 8,000 acres (3,200 ha) of municipal parkland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] There are 31 sand beaches, a plethora of museums, two world-class conservatories, and 50 nature areas.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Lincoln Park, the largest of the city's parks, covers 1,200 acres (490 ha) and has over 20 million visitors each year, making it third in the number of visitors after Central Park in New York City, and the National Mall and Memorial Parks in Washington, D.C.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] There is a historic boulevard system, a network of wide, tree-lined boulevards which connect a number of Chicago parks.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The boulevards and the parks were authorized by the Illinois legislature in 1869.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] A number of Chicago neighborhoods emerged along these roadways in the 19th century.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The building of the boulevard system continued intermittently until 1942.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] It includes nineteen boulevards, eight parks, and six squares, along twenty-six miles of interconnected streets.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The *Chicago Park Boulevard System Historic District* was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2018.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] With berths for more than 6,000 boats, the Chicago Park District operates the nation's largest municipal harbor system.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Washington Park is also one of the city's biggest parks; covering nearly 400 acres (160 ha).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The park is listed on the National Register of Historic Places listings in South Side Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The government of the City of Chicago is divided into executive and legislative branches.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The mayor of Chicago is the chief executive, elected by general election for a term of four years, with no term limits.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The mayor appoints commissioners and other officials who oversee the various departments.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] As well as the mayor, Chicago's clerk and treasurer are also elected citywide.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The City Council is the legislative branch and is made up of 50 alderpersons, one elected from each ward in the city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The council takes official action through the passage of ordinances and resolutions and approves the city budget.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Chicago Police Department provides law enforcement and the Chicago Fire Department provides fire suppression and emergency medical services for the city and its residents.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Civil and criminal law cases are heard in the Cook County Circuit Court of the State of Illinois court system, or in the Northern District of Illinois, in the federal system.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] In the state court, the public prosecutor is the Illinois state's attorney; in the Federal court it is the United States attorney.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] During much of the last half of the 19th century, Chicago's politics were dominated by a growing Democratic Party organization.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] During the 1880s and 1890s, Chicago had a powerful radical tradition with large and highly organized socialist, anarchist and labor organizations.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] For much of the 20th century, Chicago has been among the largest and most reliable Democratic strongholds in the United States; with Chicago's Democratic vote the state of Illinois has been "solid blue" in presidential elections since 1992.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Even before then, it was not unheard of for Republican presidential candidates to win handily in downstate Illinois, only to lose statewide due to large Democratic margins in Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The citizens of Chicago have not elected a Republican mayor since 1927, when William Thompson was voted into office.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The strength of the party in Chicago is partly a consequence of Illinois state politics, where the Republicans have come to represent rural and farm concerns while the Democrats support urban issues such as Chicago's public school funding.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago contains less than 25% of the state's population, but it is split between eight of Illinois' 17 districts in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] All eight of the city's representatives are Democrats; only two Republicans have represented a significant portion of the city since 1973, for one term each: Robert P.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Hanrahan from 1973 to 1975, and Michael Patrick Flanagan from 1995 to 1997.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Machine politics persisted in Chicago after the decline of similar machines in other large U.S. cities.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] During much of that time, the city administration found opposition mainly from a liberal "independent" faction of the Democratic Party.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The independents finally gained control of city government in 1983 with the election of Harold Washington (in office 1983–1987).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] From 1989 until May 16, 2011, Chicago was under the leadership of its longest-serving mayor, Richard M.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Because of the dominance of the Democratic Party in Chicago, the Democratic primary vote held in the spring is generally more significant than the general elections in November for U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The aldermanic, mayoral, and other city offices are filled through nonpartisan elections with runoffs as needed.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The city is home of former United States President Barack Obama and First Lady Michelle Obama; Barack Obama was formerly a state legislator representing Chicago and later a U.S. senator.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Obamas' residence is located near the University of Chicago in Kenwood on the city's south side.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago experienced major rises in violent crime in the 1920s, in the late 1960s, and in the 2020s.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago's biggest criminal justice challenges have changed little over the last 50 years, and statistically reside with homicide, armed robbery, gang violence, and aggravated battery.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago has a higher murder rate than the larger cities of New York and Los Angeles.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] However, while it has a large absolute number of crimes due to its size, Chicago is not among the top-25 most violent cities in the United States.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Murder rates in Chicago vary greatly depending on the neighborhood in question.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The neighborhoods of Englewood on the South Side, and Austin on the West side, for example, have homicide rates that are ten times higher than other parts of the city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago has an estimated population of over 100,000 active gang members from nearly 60 factions.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] According to reports in 2013, "most of Chicago's violent crime comes from gangs trying to maintain control of drug-selling territories," and is specifically related to the activities of the Sinaloa Cartel, which is active in several American cities.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Violent crime rates vary significantly by area of the city, with more economically developed areas having low rates, but other sections have much higher rates of crime.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] In 2013, the violent crime rate was 910 per 100,000 people; the murder rate was 10.4 per 100,000 – while high crime districts saw 38.9 murders, low crime districts saw 2.5 murders per 100,000.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago's long history of public corruption regularly draws the attention of federal law enforcement and federal prosecutors.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] From 2012 to 2019, 33 Chicago alderpersons were convicted on corruption charges, roughly one third of those elected in the time period.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] A report from the Office of the Legislative Inspector General noted that over half of Chicago's elected alderpersons took illegal campaign contributions in 2013.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Most corruption cases in Chicago are prosecuted by the U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Attorney's office, as legal jurisdiction makes most offenses punishable as a federal crime.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago Public Schools (CPS) is the governing body of the school district that contains over 600 public elementary and high schools citywide, including several selective-admission magnet schools.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] There are eleven selective enrollment high schools in the Chicago Public Schools, designed to meet the needs of Chicago's most academically advanced students.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] These schools offer a rigorous curriculum with mainly honors and Advanced Placement (AP) courses.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Walter Payton College Prep High School is ranked number one in the city of Chicago and the state of Illinois.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago high school rankings are determined by the average test scores on state achievement tests.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The district, with an enrollment exceeding 400,545 students (2013–2014 20th Day Enrollment), is the third-largest in the U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] In September 2012, teachers for the Chicago Teachers Union went on strike for the first time since 1987 over pay, resources, and other issues.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] According to 2014 data, Chicago's "choice system", where students who test or apply and may attend one of approximately 130 public high schools, sorts students of different achievement levels into different schools (high performing, middle performing, and low performing schools).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago has a network of Lutheran schools, and several private schools are run by other denominations and faiths, such as the Ida Crown Jewish Academy in West Ridge.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Chicago operates Catholic schools, including Jesuit preparatory schools and others.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] A number of private schools are completely secular.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] There is also the private Chicago Academy for the Arts, a high school focused on six different artistic disciplines, and the public Chicago High School for the Arts, a high school focused on five disciplines (visual arts, theatre, musical theatre, dance, and music).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Chicago Public Library system operates three regional libraries and 77 neighborhood branches, including the central library.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Since the 1850s, Chicago has been a world center of higher education and research with several universities.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] These institutions consistently rank among the top "National Universities" in the United States, as determined by *U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Highly regarded universities in Chicago and the surrounding area are the University of Chicago; Northwestern University; Illinois Institute of Technology; Loyola University Chicago; DePaul University; Columbia College Chicago and the University of Illinois Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] William Rainey Harper, the first president of the University of Chicago, was instrumental in the creation of the junior college concept, establishing nearby Joliet Junior College as the first in the nation in 1901.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] His legacy continues with the multiple community colleges in the Chicago proper, including the seven City Colleges of Chicago: Richard J.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Daley College, Kennedy–King College, Malcolm X College, Olive–Harvey College, Truman College, Harold Washington College, and Wilbur Wright College, in addition to the privately held MacCormac College.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The Chicago metropolitan area is a major media hub and the third-largest media market in the United States, after New York City and Los Angeles.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Each of the big five U.S. television networks, NBC, ABC, CBS, Fox and The CW, directly owns and operates a high-definition television station in Chicago (WMAQ 5, WLS 7, WBBM 2, WFLD 32 and WGN-TV 9, respectively).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] WGN is owned by the CW through a majority stake held in the network by the Nexstar Media Group, which acquired it from its founding owner Tribune Broadcasting in 2019.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] WGN was once carried, with some programming differences, as "WGN America" on cable and satellite TV nationwide and in parts of the Caribbean.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] WGN America eventually became NewsNation in 2021.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago has been the home of several prominent talk shows, including *The Oprah Winfrey Show*, *Steve Harvey Show*, *The Rosie Show*, *The Jerry Springer Show*, *The Phil Donahue Show*, *The Jenny Jones Show*, and more.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The city has one PBS member station (its second: WYCC 20, removed its affiliation with PBS in 2017): WTTW 11, producer of shows such as *Sneak Previews*, *The Frugal Gourmet*, *Lamb Chop's Play-Along* and *The McLaughlin Group*.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] As of 2018, *Windy City Live* is Chicago's only daytime talk show, which is hosted by Val Warner and Ryan Chiaverini at ABC7 Studios with a live weekday audience.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Since 1999, *Judge Mathis* also films his syndicated arbitration-based reality court show at the NBC Tower.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Beginning in January 2019, *Newsy* began producing 12 of its 14 hours of live news programming per day from its new facility in Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Most of Chicago's television stations are owned and operated by the big television network companies.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Two major daily newspapers are published in Chicago: the *Chicago Tribune* and the *Chicago Sun-Times*, with the Tribune having the larger circulation.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] The entertainment and cultural magazine *Time Out Chicago* and *GRAB* magazine are published in the city, as well as local music magazine *Chicago Innerview*.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago is the home of satirical national news outlet, *The Onion*, and its sister pop-culture publication, *The A.V.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago has five 50,000 watt AM radio stations: the Audacy-owned WBBM and WSCR; the Tribune Broadcasting-owned WGN; the Cumulus Media-owned WLS; and the ESPN Radio-owned WMVP.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] Chicago is also home to a number of national radio shows, including *Beyond the Beltway* with Bruce DuMont on Sunday evenings.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p02] WBEZ produces nationally aired programs such as PRI's *This American Life* and NPR's *Wait Wait...Don't Tell Me!*.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Chicago is a major transportation hub in the United States and North America.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] It is an important component in global distribution, as it is the third-largest inter-modal port in the world after Hong Kong and Singapore.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] The city of Chicago has a higher than average percentage of households without a car.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] In 2015, 26.5 percent of Chicago households were without a car, and increased slightly to 27.5 percent in 2016.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Chicago averaged 1.12 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Due to Chicago's wheel tax, residents of Chicago who own a vehicle are required to purchase a Chicago City Vehicle Sticker.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] In established Residential Parking Zones, only local residents can purchase Zone-specific parking stickers for themselves and guests.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Chicago since 2009 has relinquished rights to its public street parking.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] In 2008, as Chicago struggled to close a growing budget deficit, the city agreed to a 75-year, $1.16 billion deal to lease its parking meter system to an operating company created by Morgan Stanley, called Chicago Parking Meters LLC.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] The rights of the parking ticket lease end in 2081, and since 2022 have already recouped over $1.5 billion in revenue for Chicago Parking Meters LLC investors.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Eight mainline and four auxiliary interstate highways (41 (mostly in Wisconsin), 55, 57, 65 (only in Indiana), 80 (also in Indiana), 88, 90 (also in Indiana), 94 (also in Indiana), 190, 290, 294, and 355) run through Chicago and its suburbs.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] I-490 is currently under construction on the west side of O'Hare Airport.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Segments that link to the city center are named after influential politicians, with three of them named after former U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Presidents (Eisenhower, Kennedy, and Reagan) and one named after two-time Democratic candidate Adlai Stevenson.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] The Kennedy and Dan Ryan Expressways are the busiest state maintained routes in the entire state of Illinois.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] The Regional Transportation Authority (RTA) coordinates the operation of the three service boards: CTA, Metra, and Pace.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Beginning in June 2026, the RTA will be replaced by the Northern Illinois Transit Authority (NITA).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] The Northern Indiana Commuter Transportation District (NICTD) operates the South Shore Line, which provides commuter rail service from Millennium Station to Northwest Indiana.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Since March 2026, it consists of two services: the Lakeshore Corridor to South Bend and the Monon Corridor to Munster/Dyer.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Greyhound Lines provides inter-city bus service to and from the city at the Chicago Bus Station, and Chicago is also the hub for the Midwest network of Megabus.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Amtrak long distance and inter-city rail services originate from Chicago Union Station.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Chicago is one of the largest hubs of passenger rail service in the nation.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] The services terminate in Port Huron, St.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Paul, the San Francisco Area, New York City, New Orleans, Portland, Oregon, Seattle, Miami, Milwaukee, Carbondale, Quincy, Boston, St.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Louis, Kansas City, Grand Rapids, Los Angeles, San Antonio, and Pontiac, Michigan.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Future service will terminate at Moline.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Chicago has a total of four active rail terminals: Chicago Union Station, Ogilvie Transportation Center, LaSalle Street Station, and Millennium Station.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Amtrak only serves Union Station, while Metra serves all four stations.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] The South Shore Line services uses Millennium Station as its Chicago terminal.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] In July 2013, the bicycle-sharing system Divvy was launched with 750 bikes and 75 docking stations.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] It is operated by Lyft for the Chicago Department of Transportation.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] As of July 2019, Divvy operated 5800 bicycles at 608 stations, covering almost all of the city, excluding Pullman, Rosedale, Beverly, Belmont Cragin and Edison Park.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] In May 2019, The City of Chicago announced its Chicago's Electric Shared Scooter Pilot Program, scheduled to run from June 15 to October 15.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] The program started on June 15 with 10 different scooter companies, including scooter sharing market leaders Bird, Jump, Lime and Lyft.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Each company was allowed to bring 250 electric scooters, although both Bird and Lime claimed that they experienced a higher demand for their scooters.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] The program ended on October 15, with nearly 800,000 rides taken.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Chicago is the largest hub in the railroad industry.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] All five Class I railroads meet in Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] As of 2002, severe freight train congestion caused trains to take as long to get through the Chicago region as it took to get there from the West Coast of the country (about 2 days).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Department of Transportation, the volume of imported and exported goods transported via rail to, from, or through Chicago is forecast to increase nearly 150 percent between 2010 and 2040.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] CREATE, the Chicago Region Environmental and Transportation Efficiency Program, comprises about 70 programs, including crossovers, overpasses and underpasses, that intend to significantly improve the speed of freight movements in the Chicago area.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Chicago is served by O'Hare International Airport, the world's busiest airport measured by airline operations, on the far Northwest Side, and Midway International Airport on the Southwest Side.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] In 2005, O'Hare was the world's busiest airport by aircraft movements and the second-busiest by total passenger traffic.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] O'Hare is major hub for American Airlines and United Airlines.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Midway is a major operating base for Southwest Airlines.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Both O'Hare and Midway are owned and operated by the City of Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] The CTA's Blue Line provides direct rail access to O'Hare, while the Orange Line provides direct rail access to Midway.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Gary/Chicago International Airport and Chicago Rockford International Airport, located in Gary, Indiana and Rockford, Illinois, respectively, can serve as alternative Chicago area airports, however they do not offer as many commercial flights as O'Hare and Midway.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] In recent years the state of Illinois has been leaning towards building an entirely new airport in the Illinois suburbs of Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] The City of Chicago is the world headquarters for United Airlines, the world's third-largest airline.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] The Port of Chicago consists of several major port facilities within the city of Chicago operated by the Illinois International Port District (formerly known as the Chicago Regional Port District).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] The central element of the Port District, Calumet Harbor, is maintained by the U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Electricity for most of northern Illinois is provided by Commonwealth Edison, also known as ComEd.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Their service territory borders Iroquois County to the south, the Wisconsin border to the north, the Iowa border to the west and the Indiana border to the east.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] In northern Illinois, ComEd (a division of Exelon) operates the greatest number of nuclear generating plants in any U.S. state.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Because of this, ComEd reports indicate that Chicago receives about 75% of its electricity from nuclear power.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Recently, the city began installing wind turbines on government buildings to promote renewable energy.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Natural gas is provided by Peoples Gas, a subsidiary of Integrys Energy Group, which is headquartered in Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Domestic and industrial waste was once incinerated but it is now landfilled, mainly in the Calumet area.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] From 1995 to 2008, the city had a blue bag program to divert recyclable refuse from landfills.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Because of low participation in the blue bag programs, the city began a pilot program for blue bin recycling like other cities.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] This proved successful and blue bins were rolled out across the city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] The Illinois Medical District is on the Near West Side.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] It includes Rush University Medical Center, ranked as the second best hospital in the Chicago metropolitan area by *U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] News & World Report* for 2014–16, the University of Illinois Medical Center at Chicago, Jesse Brown VA Hospital, and John H.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Hospital of Cook County, one of the busiest trauma centers in the nation.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] Two of the country's premier academic medical centers, Northwestern Memorial Hospital and the University of Chicago Medical Center, reside in Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] The Chicago campus of Northwestern University includes the Feinberg School of Medicine; Northwestern Memorial Hospital, which was ranked as the best hospital in the Chicago metropolitan area by *U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] News & World Report* for 2017–18; the Shirley Ryan AbilityLab (formerly named the Rehabilitation Institute of Chicago), which was ranked the best U.S. rehabilitation hospital by *U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] News & World Report*; the new Prentice Women's Hospital; and Ann & Robert H.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] The University of Illinois College of Medicine at UIC is the second-largest medical school in the United States (2,600 students, including those at campuses in Peoria, Rockford and Urbana–Champaign).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] In addition, the Chicago Medical School and Loyola University Chicago's Stritch School of Medicine are located in the suburbs of North Chicago and Maywood, respectively.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/chicago-p03] The Midwestern University Chicago College of Osteopathic Medicine is in Downers Grove.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland was founded in 1796 near the mouth of the Cuyahoga River as part of the Connecticut Western Reserve in modern-day Northeast Ohio by General Moses Cleaveland, after whom the city was named.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's location on the river and the lake shore allowed it to grow into a major commercial and industrial metropolis by the late 19th century, attracting large numbers of immigrants and migrants.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] It was among the top 10 largest U.S. cities by population for much of the 20th century, a period that saw the development of the city's cultural institutions.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] By the 1960s, Cleveland's economy began to slow down as manufacturing declined and suburbanization occurred.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland is a port city, connected to the Atlantic Ocean via the St.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Its economy relies on diverse sectors that include higher education, manufacturing, financial services, healthcare, and biomedicals.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city serves as the headquarters of the Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland, as well as several major companies.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The GDP for Greater Cleveland was US$138.3 billion in 2022.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Combined with the Akron metropolitan area, the eight-county Cleveland–Akron metropolitan economy was $176 billion in 2022, the largest in Ohio.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Known as "The Forest City" among many other nicknames, Cleveland serves as the center of the Cleveland Metroparks nature reserve system.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's major league professional sports teams include the Cleveland Browns (football; NFL), the Cleveland Cavaliers (basketball; NBA), and the Cleveland Guardians (baseball; MLB).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland was established on July 22, 1796, by surveyors of the Connecticut Land Company when they laid out Connecticut's Western Reserve into townships and a capital city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] They named the settlement "Cleaveland" after their leader, General Moses Cleaveland, a veteran of the American Revolutionary War.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleaveland oversaw the New England–style design of the plan for what would become the modern downtown area, centered on Public Square.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The town's name was often shortened to "Cleveland", including by Cleaveland's original surveyors.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] A myth emerged that the spelling was altered by *The Cleveland Advertiser* to fit the name on the newspaper's masthead.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The first permanent European settler in Cleveland was Lorenzo Carter, who arrived in May 1797 and built a cabin on the banks of the Cuyahoga River.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The emerging community served as an important supply post for the U.S. during the Battle of Lake Erie in the War of 1812.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Largely through the efforts of the settlement's first lawyer, Alfred Kelley, the village of Cleveland was incorporated on December 23, 1814.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Despite the nearby swampy lowlands and harsh winters, the town's waterfront on Lake Erie was advantageous, giving it access to Great Lakes trade.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] It grew rapidly after the 1832 completion of the Ohio and Erie Canal, which linked the Ohio River and the Great Lakes to the Atlantic Ocean via the Erie Canal and Hudson River, and later via the Saint Lawrence Seaway.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The town's growth continued with added railroad links.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In 1836, Cleveland, then only on the eastern banks of the Cuyahoga, was incorporated as a city; John W.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The neighboring municipality of Ohio City was a major rival to Cleveland until its annexation by the city in 1854.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] A center of abolitionist activity, Cleveland (code-named "Station Hope") was a major stop on the Underground Railroad for escaped African American slaves en route to Canada.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city served as an important center for the Union during the American Civil War, creating a large manufacturing industry within the city and unprecedented growth.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Its geographic location as a transportation hub on the Great Lakes contributed to its development as an industrial and commercial center.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Rockefeller founded Standard Oil in Cleveland; in 1885, he moved its headquarters to New York City.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland's economic growth and industrial jobs attracted large waves of immigrants from Southern Europe, Eastern Europe, and Ireland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Urban growth was accompanied by labor unrest as workers demanded better wages and working conditions.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland Streetcar Strike of 1899 was one of the more violent instances of labor strife in the city during this period.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] By 1910, Cleveland had become known as the "Sixth City" due to its status at the time as the sixth-largest U.S. city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Its automotive companies included Peerless, Chandler, and Winton, maker of the first car driven across the U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Other manufacturing industries in Cleveland included steam cars produced by White and electric cars produced by Baker.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Euclid Avenue became known as "Millionaires' Row" for its prestige and elegance.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Major Progressive Era politicians were leaders in the city, including populist Mayor Tom L.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Johnson, who was responsible for the development of the Cleveland Mall Plan.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The era of the City Beautiful movement in Cleveland architecture saw wealthy patrons support the establishment of the city's major cultural institutions including the Cleveland Museum of Art, which opened in 1916, and the Cleveland Orchestra, established in 1918.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] African American migrants from the rural South arrived in Cleveland as part of the Great Migration for jobs, constitutional rights, and relief from racial discrimination.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] By 1920 Cleveland had grown into a densely populated metropolis of 796,841, making it the fifth-largest city in the nation, with a foreign-born population of 30%.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Radical labor movements gained popularity in the city, such as the Industrial Workers of the World (IWW), in response to the conditions of the largely immigrant and migrant workers.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In 1919, local socialist and IWW demonstrators clashed with anti-socialists in the May Day Riots, which occurred amid the First Red Scare and the strike wave that swept the U.S. that year.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland's population grew throughout the Roaring Twenties.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The decade saw the establishment of the city's Playhouse Square, and the rise of the risqué Short Vincent.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Bal-Masque balls of the avant-garde Kokoon Arts Club scandalized the city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Jazz came to prominence in Cleveland during this period.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Prohibition was established in Ohio in May 1919 (although it was not well-enforced in Cleveland), became law with the Volstead Act in 1920, and was repealed nationally by Congress in 1933.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The ban on alcohol led to the rise of speakeasies throughout the city and organized crime gangs, such as the Mayfield Road Mob, who smuggled bootleg liquor across Lake Erie from Canada into Cleveland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In 1929, Cleveland hosted the first of many National Air Races, and Amelia Earhart flew to the city from Santa Monica, California in the Women's Air Derby.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Van Sweringen brothers commenced construction of the Terminal Tower skyscraper in 1926 and oversaw its completion in 1927.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] When the building was dedicated as part of Cleveland Union Terminal in 1930, the city had a population of over 900,000.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland's economy was greatly effected by the Wall Street Crash of 1929 and Great Depression.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] A center of union activity, the city saw significant labor struggles in this period, including strikes by workers against Fisher Body in 1936 and against Republic Steel in 1937.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city was aided by major federal works projects sponsored by President Franklin D.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In commemoration of the centennial of Cleveland's incorporation as a city, the Great Lakes Exposition debuted in June 1936 at the city's North Coast Harbor, along the Lake Erie shore north of downtown.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Conceived by Cleveland's business leaders as a way to revitalize the city during the Depression, it drew four million visitors in its first season, and seven million by the end of its second and final season in September 1937.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] During World War II, Cleveland was a major hub of the U.S. war effort as the fifth largest manufacturing center in the nation.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] During the war the city established the Cleveland Transit System, the predecessor to the Greater Cleveland Regional Transit Authority.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland experienced an economic boom after the war and businesses declared the city to be the "best location in the nation".
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The decade saw the rising popularity of the rock and roll music genre.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] By the 1960s, Cleveland's economy slowed and residents sought new housing in the suburbs, reflecting national trends of suburban growth following federally subsidized highways.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Industrial restructuring, particularly in the steel and automotive industries, resulted in the loss of numerous jobs in Cleveland and the city suffered economically.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The burning of the Cuyahoga River in June 1969 brought national attention to the issue of industrial pollution in Cleveland and catalyzed the American environmental movement.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Housing discrimination and redlining against African Americans led to racial unrest in Cleveland; the Hough riots erupted from July 18 to 24, 1966, and the Glenville Shootout took place on July 23, 1968.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In November 1967, Cleveland became the first major American city to elect an African American mayor, Carl B.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Stokes, who worked to restore the Cuyahoga River.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] During the 1970s, Cleveland was known as "Bomb City U.S.A." due to several bombings that shook the city, mostly due to organized crime rivalries.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In December 1978, Cleveland became the first major American city since the Great Depression to enter a financial default on federal loans.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The national recession of the early 1980s eroded the city's traditional economic industries; Cleveland's unemployment rate of 13.8% was higher than the national average due to the closure of several steel production centers.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city began an economic recovery in the 1980s.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Although the city emerged from default in 1987, it suffered from the impact of the subprime mortgage crisis and the Great Recession.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] By the 21st century, Cleveland had developed a more diversified economy and gained a national reputation as a center for healthcare and the arts.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's downtown and several neighborhoods experienced significant population growth since 2010, while overall population decline has slowed.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city has a total area of 82.47 square miles (213.6 km2), of which 77.70 square miles (201.2 km2) is land and 4.77 square miles (12.4 km2) is water.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The shore of Lake Erie is 569 feet (173 m) above sea level; the city lies on a series of irregular bluffs lying roughly parallel to the lake.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In Cleveland, these bluffs are cut principally by the Cuyahoga River, Big Creek, and Euclid Creek.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The land rises quickly from the lake shore elevation of 569 feet.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Public Square, less than one mile (1.6 km) inland, sits at an elevation of 650 feet (198 m), and Hopkins Airport, five miles (8.0 km) inland from the lake, is at an elevation of 791 feet (241 m).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland borders several inner-ring and streetcar suburbs.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] To the west, it borders Lakewood, Rocky River, and Fairview Park, and to the east, it borders Shaker Heights, Cleveland Heights, South Euclid, and East Cleveland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] To the southwest, it borders Linndale, Brooklyn, Parma, and Brook Park.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] To the south, the city borders Newburgh Heights, Cuyahoga Heights, and Brooklyn Heights and to the southeast, it borders Warrensville Heights, Maple Heights, and Garfield Heights.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] To the northeast, along the shore of Lake Erie, Cleveland borders Bratenahl and Euclid.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Many of the city's government and civic buildings, including City Hall, the Cuyahoga County Courthouse, the Cleveland Public Library, and Public Auditorium, are clustered around the open Cleveland Mall and share a common neoclassical architecture.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] They were built in the early 20th century as the result of the 1903 Group Plan.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] They constitute one of the most complete examples of City Beautiful design.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Completed in 1927 and dedicated in 1930 as part of the Cleveland Union Terminal complex, the Terminal Tower is a prototypical Beaux-Arts skyscraper.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] It was the tallest building in North America outside New York City until 1964 and the tallest in the city until 1991.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Key Tower (the tallest building in Ohio) and 200 Public Square combine elements of Art Deco architecture with postmodern designs.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Nicknamed Cleveland's "Crystal Palace", the five-story Cleveland Arcade (also known as the Old Arcade) was built in 1890 and renovated in 2001 as a Hyatt Regency Hotel.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland Trust Company Building was completed in 1907 and renovated in 2015 as a downtown Heinen's supermarket.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland's historic ecclesiastical architecture includes the Presbyterian Old Stone Church, the onion-domed St.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Theodosius Russian Orthodox Cathedral, and the Roman Catholic Cathedral of St.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] John the Evangelist along with several other ethnically inspired Catholic churches.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland City Planning Commission has designated 34 neighborhoods in Cleveland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Centered on Public Square, Downtown Cleveland is the city's central business district, encompassing subdistricts such as the Nine-Twelve District, the Campus District, the Civic Center, East 4th Street, Playhouse Square, and the Short Vincent entertainment district.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Mixed-use areas, such as the Warehouse District and the Superior Arts District, are occupied by industrial and office buildings as well as restaurants, cafes, and bars.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The number of condominiums, lofts, and apartments has been on the increase since 2000 and especially 2010, reflecting downtown's growing population.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Clevelanders geographically define themselves by whether they live on the east or west side of the Cuyahoga River.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The East Side includes the neighborhoods of Buckeye–Shaker, Buckeye–Woodhill, Central, Collinwood (including Nottingham), Euclid–Green, Fairfax, Glenville, Goodrich–Kirtland Park (including Asiatown), Hough, Kinsman, Lee–Miles (including Lee–Harvard and Lee–Seville), Mount Pleasant, St.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Clair–Superior, Union–Miles Park, and University Circle (including Little Italy).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cuyahoga Valley neighborhood (including Whiskey Island and the Flats) is situated between the East and West Sides, while Broadway–Slavic Village is sometimes referred to as the South Side.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Several neighborhoods have seen the return of the middle class that left the city for the suburbs in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] These include Ohio City, Tremont, Detroit–Shoreway, and Edgewater on the West Side, and Collinwood, Hough, Fairfax, and Little Italy on the East Side.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The growth was spurred by attracting creative class members, which has facilitated new residential development and the transformation of old industrial buildings into loft spaces for artists.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland exhibits a humid continental (Köppen: *Dfa*) or humid subtropical (Köppen: *Cfa*) climate, depending on the isotherm used.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Due to its proximity to Lake Erie, Cleveland experiences milder temperatures than much of Ohio, with relatively cooler summers and warmer winters.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] East of the mouth of the Cuyahoga, the land elevation rises rapidly in the south.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Together with the prevailing winds off Lake Erie, this feature is the principal contributor to the lake-effect snow that is typical in Cleveland (especially on the city's East Side) from mid-November until the surface of the lake freezes, usually in late January or early February.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The lake effect causes a relative differential in geographical snowfall totals across the city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] On the city's far West Side, the Hopkins neighborhood only reached 100 inches (254 cm) of snowfall in a season three times since record-keeping for snow began in 1893.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] By contrast, seasonal totals approaching or exceeding 100 inches (254 cm) are not uncommon as the city ascends into the Heights on the east, where the region known as the "Snow Belt" begins.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Extending from the city's East Side and its suburbs, the Snow Belt reaches up the Lake Erie shore as far as Buffalo.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The all-time record high in Cleveland of 104 °F (40 °C) was established on June 25, 1988, and the all-time record low of −20 °F (−29 °C) was set on January 19, 1994.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] On average, July is the warmest month with a mean temperature of 74.5 °F (23.6 °C), and January, with a mean temperature of 29.1 °F (−1.6 °C), is the coldest.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Normal yearly precipitation based on the 30-year average from 1991 to 2020 is 41.03 inches (1,042 mm).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The least precipitation occurs on the western side and directly along the lake, and the most occurs in the eastern suburbs.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Parts of Geauga County to the east receive over 44 inches (1,100 mm) of liquid precipitation annually.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] With its extensive cleanup of its Lake Erie shore and the Cuyahoga River, Cleveland has been recognized by national media as an environmental success story and a national leader in environmental protection.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Since the city's industrialization, the Cuyahoga River had become so affected by industrial pollution that it "caught fire" a total of 13 times beginning in 1868.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] It was the river fire of June 1969 that spurred the city to action under Mayor Carl B.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Stokes, and played a key role in the passage of the Clean Water Act in 1972 and the National Environmental Policy Act later that year.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Since that time, the Cuyahoga has been extensively cleaned up through the efforts of the city and the Ohio Environmental Protection Agency (OEPA).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In addition to continued efforts to improve freshwater and air quality, Cleveland is now exploring renewable energy.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's two main electrical utilities are FirstEnergy and Cleveland Public Power.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Its climate action plan, updated in December 2018, has a 2050 target of 100% renewable power, along with reduction of greenhouse gases to 80% below the 2010 level.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In recent decades, Cleveland has been working to address the issue of harmful algal blooms on Lake Erie, fed primarily by agricultural runoff, which have presented new environmental challenges for the city and for northern Ohio.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland has seen a population decline over the past century.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's population was 914,808 according to the 1950 Census.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] According to the 2020 census, there were 372,624 people and 170,549 households in Cleveland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The population density was 4,901.51 inhabitants per square mile (1,892.5/km2).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The median household income was $30,907 and the per capita income was $21,223.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] 32.7% of the population was living below the poverty line.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Of the city's population over the age of 25, 17.5% held a bachelor's degree or higher, and 80.8% had a high school diploma or equivalent.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] As of 2020, the racial and ethnic composition of the city was 47.5% African American, 32.1% non-Hispanic white, 13.1% Hispanic or Latino, 2.8% Asian, 0.2% Native American, and 3.8% from two or more races.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] 85.3% of Clevelanders age five and older spoke only English at home, while 14.7% spoke a language other than English, including Spanish, Arabic, Chinese, Hungarian, Albanian, and various Slavic languages (Russian, Polish, Serbian, Croatian, and Slovene).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's spoken accent is an advanced form of Inland Northern American English, similar to other Great Lakes cities, but distinctive from the rest of Ohio.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] , now serves an African American congregation.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In the 19th and early 20th centuries, Cleveland saw a massive influx of immigrants from Ireland, Italy, and the Austro-Hungarian, German, Russian, and Ottoman empires, most of whom were attracted by manufacturing jobs.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The presence of Hungarians within Cleveland proper was, at one time, so great that the city boasted the highest concentration of Hungarians in the world outside of Budapest.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland has a long-established Jewish community, historically centered on the East Side neighborhoods of Glenville and Kinsman, but now mostly concentrated in East Side suburbs such as Cleveland Heights and Beachwood, location of the Maltz Museum of Jewish Heritage.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The availability of jobs attracted African Americans from the South.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Between 1910 and 1970, the black population of Cleveland, largely concentrated on the city's East Side, increased significantly as a result of the First and Second Great Migrations.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland's Latino community consists primarily of Puerto Ricans, as well as smaller numbers of immigrants from Mexico, Cuba, the Dominican Republic, South and Central America, and Spain.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's Asian community, centered on historical Asiatown, consists of Chinese, Koreans, Vietnamese, and other groups.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Additionally, the city and the county have significant communities of Albanians, Arabs (especially Lebanese, Syrians, and Palestinians), Armenians, French, Greeks, Iranians, Scots, Turks, and West Indians.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] A 2020 analysis found Cleveland to be the most ethnically and racially diverse major city in Ohio.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The influx of immigrants in the 19th and early 20th centuries drastically transformed Cleveland's religious landscape.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] From a homogeneous settlement of New England Protestants, it evolved into a city with a diverse religious composition.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The predominant faith among Clevelanders today is Christianity, with Jewish, Muslim, Hindu, and Buddhist minorities.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Within Cleveland, the neighborhoods with the highest foreign-born populations are Asiatown/Goodrich–Kirtland Park (32.7%), Clark–Fulton (26.7%), West Boulevard (18.5%), Brooklyn Centre (17.3%), Downtown (17.2%), University Circle (15.9%, with 20% in Little Italy), and Jefferson (14.3%).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Recent waves of immigration have brought new groups to Cleveland, including Ethiopians and South Asians, as well as immigrants from Russia and the former USSR, Southeast Europe (especially Albania), the Middle East, East Asia, and Latin America.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In the 2010s, the immigrant population of Cleveland and Cuyahoga County began to see significant growth.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] A 2019 study found Cleveland to be the city with the shortest average processing time in the nation for immigrants to become U.S. citizens.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's annual One World Day in Rockefeller Park includes a naturalization ceremony of new immigrants.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland's location on the Cuyahoga River and Lake Erie has been key to its growth as a major commercial center.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Steel and many other manufactured goods emerged as leading industries.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city has since diversified its economy in addition to its manufacturing sector.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Established in 1914, the Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland is one of 12 U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Its downtown building, located on East 6th Street and Superior Avenue, was completed in 1923 by the Cleveland architectural firm Walker and Weeks.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The headquarters of the Federal Reserve System's Fourth District, the bank employs 1,000 people and maintains branch offices in Cincinnati and Pittsburgh.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland and Cuyahoga County are home to *Fortune 500* companies Cleveland-Cliffs, Progressive, Sherwin-Williams, Parker-Hannifin, KeyCorp, and Travel Centers of America.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] NASA maintains the Glenn Research Center in Cleveland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Jones Day, one of the largest law firms in the U.S., was founded in Cleveland in 1893.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Healthcare plays a major role in Cleveland's economy.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's "Big Three" hospital systems are the Cleveland Clinic, University Hospitals, and MetroHealth.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland Clinic is the largest private employer in the state of Ohio, with a workforce of over 55,000 as of 2022.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] It carries the distinction of being one of the best hospital systems in the world.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The clinic is led by Croatian-born president and CEO Tomislav Mihaljevic and it is affiliated with Case Western Reserve University School of Medicine.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] University Hospitals includes the University Hospitals Cleveland Medical Center and its Rainbow Babies & Children's Hospital.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cliff Megerian serves as that system's CEO.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] MetroHealth on the city's west side is led by president and CEO Christine Alexander-Rager.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Formerly known as City Hospital, it operates one of two Level I trauma centers in the city, and has various locations throughout Greater Cleveland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In 2013, Cleveland's Global Center for Health Innovation opened with 235,000 square feet (21,800 m2) of display space for healthcare companies across the world.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] To take advantage of the proximity of universities and other medical centers in Cleveland, the Veterans Administration moved the region's VA hospital from suburban Brecksville to a new facility in University Circle.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland's Playhouse Square is the second largest performing arts center in the U.S. behind New York City's Lincoln Center.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] It includes the State, Palace, Allen, Hanna, and Ohio theaters.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The theaters host Broadway musicals, special concerts, speaking engagements, and other events throughout the year.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Playhouse Square's resident performing arts companies include Cleveland Ballet, the Cleveland International Film Festival, the Cleveland Play House, Cleveland State University Department of Theatre and Dance, DANCECleveland, the Great Lakes Theater Festival, and the Tri-C Jazz Fest.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] A city with strong traditions in theater and vaudeville, Cleveland has produced many renowned performers, most prominently comedian Bob Hope.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Outside Playhouse Square is Karamu House, the oldest African American theater in the nation, established in 1915.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] On the West Side, the Gordon Square Arts District in the Detroit–Shoreway neighborhood is the location of the Capitol Theatre, the Near West Theatre, and an Off-Off-Broadway playhouse, the Cleveland Public Theatre.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Dobama Theatre and the Beck Center for the Arts are based in Cleveland's streetcar suburbs of Cleveland Heights and Lakewood respectively.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland Orchestra is widely considered one of the world's finest orchestras, and often referred to as the finest in the nation.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] It is one of the "Big Five" major orchestras in the U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The orchestra plays at Severance Hall in University Circle during the winter and at Blossom Music Center in Cuyahoga Falls during the summer.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] One Playhouse Square, now the headquarters for Cleveland's public broadcasters, was initially used as the broadcast studios of WJW (AM), where disc jockey Alan Freed first popularized the term "rock and roll".
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Beginning in the 1950s, Cleveland gained a strong reputation as a key breakout market for rock music.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Its popularity in the city was so great that Billy Bass, the program director at the WMMS radio station, referred to Cleveland as "The Rock and Roll Capital of the World".
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland Agora Theatre and Ballroom has served as a major venue for rock concerts in the city since the 1960s.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] From 1974 through 1980, the city hosted the World Series of Rock at Cleveland Municipal Stadium.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Jazz and R&B have a long history in Cleveland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Many major figures in jazz performed in the city, including Louis Armstrong, Cab Calloway, Duke Ellington, Ella Fitzgerald, Dizzy Gillespie, and Billie Holiday.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Legendary pianist Art Tatum regularly played in Cleveland clubs in the 1930s, and gypsy jazz guitarist Django Reinhardt gave his U.S. debut performance in Cleveland in 1946.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Prominent jazz artist Noble Sissle was a graduate of Cleveland Central High School, and Artie Shaw worked and performed in Cleveland early in his career.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Tri-C Jazz Fest has been held annually in Cleveland at Playhouse Square since 1980, and the Cleveland Jazz Orchestra was established in 1984.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city has a history of polka music being popular both past and present and is the location of the Polka Hall of Fame.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] A subgenre called Cleveland-style polka, named after the city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The music's popularity is due in part to the success of Frankie Yankovic, a Cleveland native who was considered "America's Polka King".
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The first film shot in Cleveland was in 1897 by the company of Ohioan Thomas Edison.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Before Hollywood became the center for American cinema, filmmaker Samuel Brodsky and playwright Robert McLaughlin operated a film studio at the Andrews mansion on Euclid Avenue (now the WEWS-TV studio).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] There they produced major silent-era features, such as *Dangerous Toys* (1921), which are now considered lost.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Brodsky also directed the weekly *Plain Dealer Screen Magazine* that ran in theaters in Cleveland and Ohio from 1917 to 1924.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In addition, Cleveland hosted over a dozen sponsored film studios, including Cinécraft Productions, which still operates in Ohio City.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In the "talkie" era, Cleveland featured in several major studio films, such as Michael Curtiz's pre-Code classic *Goodbye Again* (1933) with Warren William and Joan Blondell.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Players from the 1948 Cleveland Indians appeared in *The Kid from Cleveland* (1949).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Billy Wilder's *The Fortune Cookie* (1966) was set and filmed in the city and marked the first onscreen pairing of Walter Matthau and Jack Lemmon.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Labor struggles in Cleveland were depicted in *Native Land* (1942), narrated by Paul Robeson, and in Norman Jewison's *F.I.S.T.* (1978) with Sylvester Stallone.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Clevelander Jim Jarmusch's *Stranger Than Paradise* (1984) – a deadpan comedy about two New Yorkers who travel to Florida by way of Cleveland – was a favorite of the Cannes Film Festival.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] *Major League* (1989) reflected the perennial struggles of the Cleveland Indians, while *American Splendor* (2003) reflected the life of Cleveland graphic novelist Harvey Pekar.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] *Kill the Irishman* (2011) depicted the 1970s turf war between Danny Greene and the Cleveland crime family.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland has doubled for other locations in films.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The wedding and reception scenes in *The Deer Hunter* (1978), while set in suburban Pittsburgh, were shot in Cleveland's Tremont neighborhood.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] *A Christmas Story* (1983) was set in Indiana, but drew many external shots from Cleveland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The opening shots of *Air Force One* (1997) were filmed in and above Severance Hall, and *Judas and the Black Messiah* (2021) was filmed in Cleveland, although set in Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Downtown Cleveland doubled for Manhattan in *Spider-Man 3* (2007), *The Avengers* (2012), and *The Fate of the Furious* (2017), and for Metropolis in James Gunn's *Superman* (2025).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Future productions are handled by the Greater Cleveland Film Commission at the Leader Building on Superior Avenue.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In television, the city is the setting for the popular network sitcom *The Drew Carey Show*, starring Cleveland native Drew Carey.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] *Hot in Cleveland*, a comedy that aired on TV Land, premiered on June 16, 2010, and ran for six seasons until its finale on June 3, 2015.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] *Cleveland Hustles*, the CNBC reality show co-created by LeBron James, was filmed in the city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland has a thriving literary and poetry community, with regular poetry readings at bookstores, coffee shops, and various other venues.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In 1925, Russian Futurist poet Vladimir Mayakovsky came to Cleveland and gave a poetry recitation to the city's ethnic working class, as part of his trip to America.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland State University Poetry Center serves as an academic center for poetry in the city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Langston Hughes, preeminent poet of the Harlem Renaissance and child of an itinerant couple, lived in Cleveland as a teenager and attended Central High School in Cleveland in the 1910s.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] At Central High, the young writer was taught by Helen Maria Chesnutt, daughter of Cleveland-born African American novelist Charles W.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Hughes authored some of his earliest poems, plays, and short stories in Cleveland and contributed to the school newspaper.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The African American avant-garde poet Russell Atkins lived in the city as well.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The American modernist poet Hart Crane was born in nearby Garrettsville, Ohio in 1899.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] His adolescence was divided between Cleveland and Akron before he moved to New York City in 1916.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland was the home of Joe Shuster and Jerry Siegel, who created the comic book character Superman in 1933.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Harlan Ellison, noted author of speculative fiction, was born in Cleveland in 1934.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] As a young man, he published a series of short stories appearing in the *Cleveland News*, and performed in a number of productions for the Cleveland Play House.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland is the site of the Anisfield-Wolf Book Award, which recognizes books that have contributed to the understanding of racism and human diversity.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Presented by the Cleveland Foundation, it remains the only American book prize focusing on works that address racism and diversity.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland Museum of Art is a major American art museum, with a collection that includes more than 60,000 works of art.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Museum of Contemporary Art Cleveland showcases established and emerging artists, particularly from the Cleveland area, through hosting and producing temporary exhibitions.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Both museums offer free admission to visitors.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The two museums are part of Cleveland's University Circle, a 550-acre (2.2 km2) concentration of cultural, educational, and medical institutions located 5 miles (8.0 km) east of downtown.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In addition to the art museums, the neighborhood includes the Cleveland Botanical Garden, Case Western Reserve University, University Hospitals, Severance Hall, the Maltz Performing Arts Center, the Cleveland Museum of Natural History, and the Western Reserve Historical Society.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Also located at University Circle is the Cleveland Cinematheque at the Cleveland Institute of Art.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Pei-designed Rock and Roll Hall of Fame is located on Cleveland's Lake Erie waterfront at North Coast Harbor downtown.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Neighboring attractions include Cleveland Browns Stadium, the Great Lakes Science Center, the Steamship Mather Museum, the International Women's Air & Space Museum, and the USS *Cod*, a World War II submarine.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Scofield, the Soldiers' and Sailors' Monument at Public Square is Cleveland's major Civil War memorial and a major attraction in the city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Other city attractions include Grays Armory, the Cleveland Masonic Temple, and the Children's Museum of Cleveland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] A Cleveland holiday attraction, especially for fans of Jean Shepherd's *A Christmas Story*, is the Christmas Story House and Museum in Tremont.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland hosts the WinterLand holiday display lighting festival annually at Public Square.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland International Film Festival has been held in the city since 1977, and the Cleveland Silent Film Festival has been held since 2022.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland National Air Show, an indirect successor to the National Air Races, has been held at the city's Burke Lakefront Airport since 1964.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Great Lakes Burning River Fest, a two-night music and beer festival at Whiskey Island, has been sponsored by the Great Lakes Brewing Company since 2001.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Many ethnic festivals are held in Cleveland throughout the year.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] These include the annual Feast of the Assumption in Little Italy, Russian Maslenitsa in Rockefeller Park, the Puerto Rican Parade and Cultural Festival in Clark–Fulton, the Cleveland Asian Festival in Asiatown, the Tremont Greek Fest, and the St.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland also hosts annual Polish Dyngus Day and Slovene Kurentovanje celebrations.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's annual Saint Patrick's Day parade brings hundreds of thousands to the streets of Downtown.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland Thyagaraja Festival held each spring at Cleveland State University is the largest Indian classical music and dance festival in the world outside of India.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Since 1946, the city has annually marked One World Day in the Cleveland Cultural Gardens in Rockefeller Park, celebrating all of its ethnic communities.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland's mosaic of ethnic communities and their various culinary traditions have long played an important role in defining the city's cuisine.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Local mainstays include an abundance of Slavic, Hungarian, and Central-Eastern European contributions, such as kielbasa, stuffed cabbage, pierogies, goulash, and chicken paprikash.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Italian, German, Irish, and Jewish cuisines are also prominent in Cleveland, as are Lebanese, Greek, Chinese, Puerto Rican, Mexican, and numerous other ethnic cuisines.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Vendors at the West Side Market in Ohio City offer many ethnic foods for sale.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In addition, the city boasts a vibrant barbecue and soul food scene.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Slyman's Deli on Cleveland's near East Side is notable for its corned beef sandwich, with patrons including former U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Another celebrated sandwich, the Polish Boy, is a popular street food and Cleveland original frequently sold at downtown hot dog carts and stadium concession stands.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Brown stadium mustard is synonymous with Cleveland, especially Bertman Original Ballpark Mustard.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Another notable local food item with Depression-era roots is city chicken.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] With its blue-collar roots well intact, and plenty of Lake Erie perch and walleye available, the tradition of Friday night fish fries remains alive and thriving in Cleveland, particularly in ethnic parish-based settings, especially during the season of Lent.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Clambakes are likewise embedded into the city's culinary culture.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] For dessert, the Cleveland Cassata Cake is a unique treat invented in the local Italian community and served in Italian establishments throughout the city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Another popular dessert, the locally crafted Russian Tea Biscuit, is common in many Jewish bakeries in Cleveland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland is noted in the world of celebrity food culture.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Famous local figures include chef Michael Symon and food writer Michael Ruhlman, both of whom achieved local and national attention for their contributions to the culinary world.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] In 2007, Symon helped gain the spotlight when he was named "The Next Iron Chef" on the Food Network.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] That same year, Ruhlman collaborated with Anthony Bourdain, to do an episode of his *Anthony Bourdain: No Reservations* focusing on Cleveland's restaurant scene.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Ohio produces the fifth most beer in the U.S., with its largest brewery being Cleveland's Great Lakes Brewing Company.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland has had a long history of brewing, tied to many of its ethnic immigrants, and has reemerged as a regional leader in production.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Dozens of breweries exist within city limits, including large producers such as Market Garden Brewery.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Although breweries can be found throughout the city, the highest concentration is in the Ohio City neighborhood.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland hosts expansions from other countries as well, including the Scottish BrewDog and German Hofbrauhaus.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland's major professional sports teams are the Cleveland Guardians (Major League Baseball), the Cleveland Browns (National Football League), and the Cleveland Cavaliers (National Basketball Association).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Other professional teams include the Cleveland Monsters (American Hockey League), the Cleveland Charge (NBA G League), the Cleveland Crunch (Major League Indoor Soccer), Cleveland SC (National Premier Soccer League), and the Cleveland Fusion (Women's Football Alliance).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Local sporting venues include Progressive Field, Huntington Bank Field, Rocket Arena, the Wolstein Center, and Public Auditorium.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Cleveland Guardians – known as the Indians from 1915 to 2021 – won the World Series in 1920 and 1948.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] They also won the American League pennant, making the World Series in the 1954, 1995, 1997, and 2016 seasons.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Between 1995 and 2001, the team sold out 455 consecutive games, a Major League Baseball record that stood until 2008.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Historically, the Browns have been among the most successful franchises in American football history, winning eight titles during a short period of time – 1946, 1947, 1948, 1949, 1950, 1954, 1955, and 1964.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Browns have never played in a Super Bowl, getting close five times by making it to the NFL/AFC Championship Game in 1968, 1969, 1986, 1987, and 1989.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Former owner Art Modell's relocation of the Browns after the 1995 season caused tremendous heartbreak and resentment among local fans.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] After a series of lawsuits, a compromise was reached between Modell, Cleveland mayor Michael R.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] White, and NFL and Commissioner Paul Tagliabue to bring back the Browns beginning in the 1999 season, retaining all team history.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] In Cleveland's earlier football history, the Cleveland Bulldogs won the NFL Championship in 1924, and the Cleveland Rams won the NFL Championship in 1945 before relocating to Los Angeles.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Cavaliers won the Eastern Conference in 2007, 2015, 2016, 2017 and 2018 but were defeated in the NBA Finals by the San Antonio Spurs and then by the Golden State Warriors, respectively.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Cavs won the Conference again in 2016 and won their first NBA Championship coming back from a 3–1 deficit, finally defeating the Golden State Warriors.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Afterwards, over 1.3 million people attended a parade held in the Cavs' honor on June 22, 2016, in downtown Cleveland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Previously, the Cleveland Rosenblums dominated the original American Basketball League, and the Cleveland Pipers, owned by George Steinbrenner, won the American Basketball League championship in 1962.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Cleveland Monsters of the American Hockey League won the 2016 Calder Cup.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] They were the first Cleveland AHL team to do so since the 1964 Barons.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Collegiately, NCAA Division I Cleveland State Vikings have 19 varsity sports, nationally known for their Cleveland State Vikings men's basketball team.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] NCAA Division III Case Western Reserve Spartans have 17 varsity sports, most known for their Case Western Reserve Spartans football team.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The headquarters of the Mid-American Conference (MAC) are in Cleveland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The conference stages both its men's and women's basketball tournaments at Rocket Arena.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Cleveland Marathon has been hosted annually since 1978, and a monument commemorating one of Cleveland's most prominent track and field athletes, Jesse Owens, stands at the city's Fort Huntington Park.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The second American Chess Congress, a predecessor to the U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Championship, was held in Cleveland in 1871, and won by George Henry Mackenzie.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Open Chess Championships took place in the city, and were won by Edward Lasker and Bobby Fischer, respectively.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] In 2014, Cleveland hosted the ninth official Gay Games ceremony.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] In July 2024, the city hosted the Pan American Masters Games.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Known locally as the "Emerald Necklace", the Olmsted-inspired Cleveland Metroparks encircle Cleveland and Cuyahoga County.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The city proper encompasses the Metroparks' Brookside and Lakefront Reservations, as well as significant parts of the Rocky River, Washington, and Euclid Creek Reservations.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Lakefront Reservation, which provides public access to Lake Erie, consists of four parks: Edgewater Park, Whiskey Island–Wendy Park, East 55th Street Marina, and Gordon Park.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Three more parks fall under the jurisdiction of the Euclid Creek Reservation: Euclid Beach, Villa Angela, and Wildwood Marina.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Further south, bike and hiking trails in the Brecksville and Bedford Reservations, along with Garfield Park, provide access to trails in the Cuyahoga Valley National Park.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Also included in the Metroparks system is the Cleveland Metroparks Zoo, established in 1882.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Located in Big Creek Valley, the zoo has one of the largest collections of primates in North America.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] In addition to the Metroparks, the Cleveland Public Parks District oversees the city's neighborhood parks, the largest of which is the historic Rockefeller Park.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The latter is notable for its late 19th century landmark bridges, the Rockefeller Park Greenhouse, and the Cleveland Cultural Gardens, which celebrate the city's ethnic diversity.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Just outside of Rockefeller Park, the Cleveland Botanical Garden in University Circle, established in 1930, is the oldest civic garden center in the nation.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] In addition, the Greater Cleveland Aquarium, located in the historic FirstEnergy Powerhouse in the Flats, is the only independent, free-standing aquarium in the state of Ohio.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland operates on a mayor–council (strong mayor) form of government, in which the mayor is the chief executive and the city council serves as the legislative branch.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] City council members are elected from 15 wards to four-year terms.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] From 1924 to 1931, the city briefly experimented with a council–manager government under William R.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Morgan before returning to the mayor–council system.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland is served by Cleveland Municipal Court, the first municipal court in the state.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] District Court for the Northern District of Ohio, based at the Carl B.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Chief Judge for the Northern District is Sara Elizabeth Lioi and the Clerk of Court is Sandy Opacich.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The office of the mayor has been held by Justin Bibb since 2022.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Previous mayors include progressive Democrat Tom L.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Johnson, World War I-era War Secretary and BakerHostetler founder Newton D.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Supreme Court Justice Harold Hitz Burton, two-term Ohio Governor and Senator Frank J.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Health, Education, and Welfare Secretary Anthony J.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Celebrezze, two-term Ohio Governor and Senator George Voinovich, former U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Congressman Dennis Kucinich, and Carl B.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Stokes, the first African American mayor of a major U.S. city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Jackson was the city's longest-serving mayor.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The President of Cleveland City Council is Blaine Griffin, the council Majority Leader is Jasmin Santana, and the Majority Whip is Charles Slife.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Patricia Britt serves as the Clerk of Council.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Historically, from the Civil War era to the 1940s, Cleveland had been dominated by the Republican Party, with the notable exceptions of the Johnson and Baker mayoral administrations.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Businessman and Senator Mark Hanna was among Cleveland's most influential Republican figures, both locally and nationally.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Another nationally prominent Ohio Republican, former U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Garfield, was born in Cuyahoga County's Orange Township (today the Cleveland suburb of Moreland Hills).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Garfield Memorial in Cleveland's Lake View Cemetery.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Today Cleveland is a major stronghold for the Democratic Party in Ohio.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Although local elections are nonpartisan, Democrats still dominate every level of government.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Politically, Cleveland and several of its neighboring suburbs comprise Ohio's 11th congressional district.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The district is represented by Shontel Brown, one of five Democrats representing the state of Ohio in the U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland has hosted three Republican national conventions, in 1924, 1936, and 2016.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Additionally, the city hosted the 1864 Radical Democratic National Convention.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Although Cleveland has not hosted a national convention for the Democrats, it has hosted several national election debates, including the second 1980 U.S. presidential debate, the 2004 U.S. vice presidential debate, one 2008 Democratic primary debate, and the first 2020 U.S. presidential debate.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Founded in 1912, the City Club of Cleveland provides a platform for national and local debates and discussions.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Known as Cleveland's "Citadel of Free Speech", it is one of the oldest continuous independent free speech and debate forums in the country.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The current Safety Director for the city of Cleveland is Dornat "Wayne" Drummond.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Like in other major American cities, crime in Cleveland is concentrated in areas with higher rates of poverty and lower access to jobs.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] In recent decades, the rate of crime in the city, although higher than the national average, experienced a significant decline, following a nationwide trend in falling crime rates.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] However, as in other major U.S. cities, crime in Cleveland saw an abrupt rise in 2020–21.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland's law enforcement agency is the Cleveland Division of Police, established in 1866.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The division had roughly 1,100 sworn officers as of 2024, covering five police districts.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The district system was introduced in the 1930s by Cleveland Public Safety Director Eliot Ness (of the Untouchables), who later ran for mayor of Cleveland in 1947.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] In addition, the Cuyahoga County Sheriff's Office is based in Downtown Cleveland at the Justice Center Complex.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland is served by the firefighters of the Cleveland Division of Fire, established in 1863.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The fire department operates out of 22 active fire stations throughout the city in five battalions.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Each Battalion is commanded by a Battalion Chief, who reports to an on-duty Assistant Chief.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Division of Fire operates a fire apparatus fleet of twenty-two engine companies, eight ladder companies, three tower companies, two task force rescue squad companies, hazardous materials ("haz-mat") unit, and numerous other special, support, and reserve units.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The interim Chief of Department is Wayne Naida.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland EMS is operated by the city as its own municipal third-service EMS division.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland EMS is the primary provider of Advanced Life Support and ambulance transport within the city of Cleveland, while Cleveland Fire assists by providing fire response medical care.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Although a merger between the fire and EMS departments was proposed in the past, the idea was subsequently abandoned.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The EMS Commissioner is Orlando Wheeler.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland serves as headquarters to Coast Guard District 9 and is responsible for all U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Coast Guard operations on the five Great Lakes, the Saint Lawrence Seaway, and surrounding states accumulating 6,700 miles of shoreline and 1,500 miles of international shoreline with Canada.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Station Cleveland Harbor, located in North Coast Harbor, has a responsibility covering about 550 square miles of the federally navigable waters of Lake Erie, including the Cuyahoga and Rocky rivers, as well as a number of their tributaries.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland is served by the Cleveland Metropolitan School District.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] It is the only K–12 district in Ohio under the direct control of the mayor, who appoints a school board.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Approximately 1 square mile (2.6 km2) of Cleveland's Buckeye–Shaker neighborhood is part of the Shaker Heights City School District.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The area, which has been a part of the Shaker school district since the 1920s, permits these Cleveland residents to pay the same school taxes as the Shaker residents, as well as vote in the Shaker school board elections.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] There are several private and parochial schools in Cleveland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] These include Benedictine High School, Cleveland Central Catholic High School, Eleanor Gerson School, St.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland is home to a number of colleges and universities.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Most prominent among them is Case Western Reserve University (CWRU), a widely recognized research and teaching institution based in University Circle with several major graduate programs.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] University Circle also contains the Cleveland Institute of Art and the Cleveland Institute of Music.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Downtown Cleveland is home to Cleveland State University, a public research university with eight constituent colleges, and the metropolitan campus of Cuyahoga Community College.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Ohio Technical College is also based in Cleveland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland's suburban universities and colleges include Baldwin Wallace University in Berea, John Carroll University in University Heights, and Ursuline College in Pepper Pike.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Established in 1869, the Cleveland Public Library is one of the largest public libraries in the nation with a collection of over 13 million materials in 2023.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] It holds the Northeast Ohio Broadcast Archives, and the John G.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] White Special Collection, with the largest chess library in the world and a rare collection of folklore and books on the Middle East and Eurasia.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The library's main building was designed by Walker and Weeks and dedicated in 1925, under head librarian Linda Eastman, the first woman to lead a major library system in the U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Between 1904 and 1920, 15 libraries built with funds from Andrew Carnegie were opened in the city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Known as the "People's University", the library presently maintains 27 branches.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] It serves as the headquarters for the CLEVNET library consortium, which includes 47 public library systems in Northeast Ohio.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland's primary daily newspaper is *The Plain Dealer* and its associated online publication, *Cleveland.com*.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Defunct major newspapers include the *Cleveland Press* and the *Cleveland News*.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Additional publications include *Cleveland Magazine*, a regional culture magazine published monthly; *Crain's Cleveland Business*, a weekly business newspaper; and *Cleveland Scene*, a free alternative weekly paper which absorbed its competitor, the *Cleveland Free Times*, in 2008.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The digital *Belt Magazine* was founded in Cleveland in 2013.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] *Time* magazine was published in Cleveland from 1925 to 1927.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Several ethnic publications are based in Cleveland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Cleveland-area television market is served by 11 full power stations, including WKYC (NBC), WEWS-TV (ABC), WJW (Fox), WDLI-TV (Bounce), WOIO (CBS), WVPX-TV (Ion), WVIZ (PBS), WUAB (MyNetworkTV), WRLM (TCT), WBNX-TV (CW), and WQHS-DT (Univision).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] As of 2021, the market, which includes the Akron and Canton areas, was the 19th-largest in the country, as measured by Nielsen Media Research.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland is directly served by 29 full power AM and FM radio stations, 21 of which are licensed to the city.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] WMMS also serves as the FM flagship for the Cleveland Cavaliers and the Cleveland Guardians, WNCX is an FM flagship for the Cleveland Browns, and WJMO is the Spanish flagship for the Browns and Cavaliers.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] News/talk stations include WHK, WTAM, and WERE.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] During the Golden Age of Radio, WHK was the first radio station to broadcast in Ohio, and one of the first in the country.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] WTAM is the AM flagship for both the Cleveland Cavaliers and the Cleveland Guardians.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Sports stations include WKNR (ESPN), WARF (Fox/VSiN) and WKRK-FM (WW1), with WKNR and WKRK-FM serving as co-flagship stations for the Cleveland Browns, and WARF – though primarily an English language station – airing Spanish broadcasts of Cleveland Guardians home games.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Religious stations include WHKW, WCCR, and WCRF.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] As the regional NPR affiliate, WKSU serves all of Northeast Ohio (including both the Cleveland and Akron markets).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] College stations include WBWC (Baldwin Wallace), WJCU (John Carroll), and WRUW-FM (Case Western Reserve).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland has a bus and rail mass transit system operated by the Greater Cleveland Regional Transit Authority (RTA).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The rail portion is officially called the RTA Rapid Transit, but local residents refer to it as *The Rapid*.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] It consists of three light rail lines, known as the Blue, Green, and Waterfront Lines, and a heavy rail line, the Red Line.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] In 2008, RTA completed the HealthLine, a bus rapid transit line, for which naming rights were purchased by the Cleveland Clinic and University Hospitals.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] It runs along Euclid Avenue from downtown through University Circle, ending at the Louis Stokes Station at Windermere in East Cleveland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] In 1968, Cleveland became the first city in the nation to have a direct rail transit connection linking the city's downtown to its major airport.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] In 2021, Walk Score ranked Cleveland the 17th most walkable of the 50 largest cities in the U.S., with a Walk Score of 57, a Transit Score of 45, and a Bike Score of 55 (out of a maximum of 100).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland's most walkable areas can be found in the Downtown, Ohio City, Detroit–Shoreway, University Circle, and Buckeye–Shaker neighborhoods.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Like other major cities, the urban density of Cleveland reduces the need for private vehicle ownership.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] In 2016, 23.7% of Cleveland households lacked a car, while the national average was 8.7%.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland averaged 1.19 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland's road system consists of numbered streets running roughly north–south, and named avenues, which run roughly east–west.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The numbered streets are designated "east" or "west", depending on where they lie in relation to Ontario Street, which bisects Public Square.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The two downtown avenues which span the Cuyahoga change names on the west side of the river.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Superior Avenue becomes Detroit Avenue on the West Side, and Carnegie Avenue becomes Lorain Avenue.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The bridges that make these connections are the Hope Memorial (Lorain–Carnegie) Bridge and the Veterans Memorial (Detroit–Superior) Bridge.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland is served by three two-digit interstate highways – I-71, I-77, and I-90 – and by two three-digit interstates – I-480 and I-490.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Running due east–west through the West Side suburbs, I-90 turns northeast at the junction with I-490, and is known as the Cleveland Inner Belt.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Cleveland Memorial Shoreway carries SR 2 along its length, and at varying points carries US 6, US 20 and I-90.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] At the junction with the Shoreway, I-90 makes a 90-degree turn in the area known as Dead Man's Curve, then continues northeast.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Jennings Freeway (SR 176) connects I-71 just south of I-90 to I-480.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] A third highway, the Berea Freeway (SR 237 in part), connects I-71 to the airport and forms part of the boundary between Brook Park and Cleveland's Hopkins neighborhood.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland is a major North American air market, serving 4.93 million people.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland Hopkins International Airport is the city's primary major airport and an international airport that serves the broader region.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Originally known as Cleveland Municipal Airport, it was the first municipally owned airport in the country.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland Hopkins is a significant regional air freight hub hosting FedEx Express, UPS Airlines, U.S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Postal Service, and major commercial freight carriers.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] In addition to Hopkins, Cleveland is served by Burke Lakefront Airport, on the north shore of downtown between Lake Erie and the Shoreway.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Burke is primarily a commuter and business airport.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Port of Cleveland, at the Cuyahoga River's mouth, is a major bulk freight and container terminal on Lake Erie, receiving much of the raw materials used by the region's manufacturing industries.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Port of Cleveland is the only container port on the Great Lakes with bi-weekly container service between Cleveland and the Port of Antwerp in Belgium on a Dutch service called the Cleveland-Europe Express.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] In addition to freight, the Port of Cleveland welcomes regional and international tourists who pass through the city on Great Lakes cruises.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland has a long history as a major railroad hub in North America.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Today, Amtrak provides service to Cleveland, via the *Capitol Limited* and *Lake Shore Limited* routes, which stop at Cleveland Lakefront Station.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Additionally, Cleveland hosts several inter-modal freight railroad terminals, for Norfolk Southern, CSX and several smaller companies.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] National intercity bus service is provided by Greyhound from its downtown bus station.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Akron Metro, Brunswick Transit Alternative, Laketran, Lorain County Transit, and Medina County Transit provide connecting bus service to the Greater Cleveland Regional Transit Authority.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Geauga County Transit and Portage Area Regional Transportation Authority (PARTA) also offer connecting bus service in their neighboring areas.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland maintains cultural, economic, and educational ties with 27 sister cities around the world.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] It concluded its first sister city partnership with Lima, Peru, in 1964.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] In addition, Cleveland hosts the Consulate General of the Republic of Slovenia, which, until Slovene independence in 1991, served as an official consulate for Tito's Yugoslavia.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Cleveland Clinic operates the Cleveland Clinic Abu Dhabi hospital, two outpatient clinics in Toronto, and a hospital campus in London.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Cleveland Council on World Affairs was established in 1923.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Historically, Cleveland industrialist Cyrus S.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] Rockefeller, played a significant role in promoting dialogue between the U.S. and the Soviet Union during the Cold War.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/cleveland-ohio-p02] In October 1915 at Cleveland's Bohemian National Hall, Czech American and Slovak American representatives signed the Cleveland Agreement, calling for the formation of a joint Czech and Slovak state.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/emo-trade-show] The name *EMO* came from the name Exposition Mondiale de la Machine-Outil (Machine Tool World Exposition), and the scope of the content still reflects the machine tool heritage, although it now also extends beyond it.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/emo-trade-show] The show covers the spectrum of metalworking technologies, such as machine tools for milling, turning, and forming; manufacturing systems; precision measuring tools; automated materials handling; computer technology; industrial electronics; and accessories.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/emo-trade-show] EMO is run by CECIMO, the European Association of the Machine Tool Industries (Comité européen de coopération des industries de la machine-outil) (www.cecimo.eu).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/emo-trade-show] EMO began as the EEMO (Exposition européenne de machines-outils, European machine tools exhibition).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/emo-trade-show] The name changed in 1975 to EMO (Exposition Mondiale de la Machine-Outil).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/emo-trade-show] Nowadays its scope extends beyond machine tools, and the acronym expansion is not used by CECIMO anymore.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/international-manufacturing-technology-show] The **International Manufacturing Technology Show** (**IMTS**), first held in Cleveland, Ohio in 1927 , is a trade show that features industrial machinery and technology.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/international-manufacturing-technology-show] It is the largest manufacturing technology trade show in North America, and in 1990 was renamed from the original "International Machine Tool Show" to reflect the growing scope of the show to additional technologies such as welding, lubrication, and materials engineering.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/international-manufacturing-technology-show] The show is managed by the Association for Manufacturing Technology.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/international-manufacturing-technology-show] The six-day show is held in even-numbered years at Chicago's McCormick Place and draws attendees and exhibitors from the U.S. and some 119 other countries.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/international-manufacturing-technology-show] IMTS was cancelled in 2020 due to the COVID-19 pandemic, but reconvened for 2022.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/international-manufacturing-technology-show] For 2018, there were 129,415 registrants and 2,563 exhibitors across four buildings and 1,424,232 square feet (132,315.5 m2) of exhibit space.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/international-manufacturing-technology-show] Since 2004, IMTS has sponsored the Emerging Technology Center, where the latest academic and industrial advancements are showcased.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/international-manufacturing-technology-show] IMTS 2012, for example, featured a Local Motors Rally Fighter car built live on the show floor, MTConnect, the open-source communication and interconnectivity standard, and MT*Insight*, the game-changing customized manufacturing business intelligence system.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] Co-creation was a technique employed by Local Motors to accelerate new product development and commercialization.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] Co-creation involves brands collaborating with customers to enhance products and services.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] Local Motors revolutionized this process through a web-based platform hosting design challenges and engineering hackathons.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] They partnered with companies such as Siemens to offer professional design tools like CAD to the community at affordable prices.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] In addition to cocreating its own proprietary products, Local Motors partnered with select organizations to facilitate co-creation of their products, including Airbus, GE, BMW, IBM, Goodyear, Reebok, Peterbilt, DARPA, Shell, US Army, ARPA-E, and Domino's.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] Local Motors' achievements in swiftly and affordably developing and bringing products to market drew interest from partners in neighboring industries eager to employ its crowdsourcing and advanced manufacturing techniques.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] Among these partners were companies like Airbus and GE, who, in turn, became significant investors in Local Motors.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] The company’s innovative business model has been referenced widely in academia, featured in hundreds of media outlets, and is the subject of a Harvard Business School (HBS) case study.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] Fast Company twice included Local Motors on its list of the world’s most innovative companies.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] The company holds three Guinness World Records and won two Popular Mechanics Breakthrough Awards.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] The Rally Fighter was introduced in 2009, as the first car to be developed using co-creation design.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] The exterior design was submitted by Sangho Kim and selected through community votes.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] In collaboration with Cincinnati Incorporated and Oak Ridge National Laboratory Local Motors manufactured Strati, the world's first 3D printed electric car.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] The printing took 44 hours to complete, and was witnessed by a live audience at the 2014 International Manufacturing Technology Show in McCormick Place, Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] The car consists of 50 individual parts, far less than a traditional vehicle (which is manufactured with roughly 30,000 parts).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] The Strati was designed by Michele Anoè, a member of the Local Motors community, and is produced in small quantities to serve strategic partnerships, such as with NXP Semiconductors.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] Strati gained widespread recognition and numerous accolades, including an SXSW Innovation Award, a Popular Mechanics Breakthrough Award, and a Guinness World Record.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] In 2015, the company debuted a 3D-printed car named the LM3D Swim.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] It was designed by Kevin Lo, a member of the Local Motors community.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] The materials used are 80 percent ABS plastic and 20 percent carbon fiber.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] The vehicle uses technology provided by IBM that offered IoT connectivity.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] The Swim is currently on display at the company's location in National Harbor, Maryland.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] In 2016, the company unveiled an autonomous, electric-powered bus.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] The vehicle was designed by Edgar Sarmiento, initially named the "Berlino" from the Urban Mobility Challenge: Berlin 2030.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] The French tech entrepreneurs Damien Declerq and Gunnar Graef have been instrumental in organizing the challenge in Berlin.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] Local Motors built the vehicle and has IBM Watson technology installed to provide a personalized experience for riders.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] The vehicle was demonstrated live to their online audience on Facebook Live at a media event in National Harbor.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] On January 2, 2018, Local Motors received a pledge of up to a $1 billion in financing and operational support to customers of Olli from Florida-based Elite Transportation Services (ETS) with additional funding of $20 million from Texas-based Xcelerate.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] Olli was manufactured in Knoxville, Tennessee, using additive manufacturing techniques, including 3D Printing.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] Traditional Steel-Tube chassis Olli vehicles were produced in Chandler, Arizona.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] Miami-Dade County, the State of Nevada and the Danish Vesthimmerland Municipality expressed interest in using Olli on their roadways.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] As of January 2020, Olli has been deployed at the United Nations ITCILO campus in Turin, Italy to provide transport shuttles to employees and guests within the campus.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] On December 17, 2021, an Olli bus operated by Durham Region Transit in Whitby, Ontario, being driven in manual mode, suddenly lost control and crashed into a tree.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] The attendant was critically injured and rushed to a trauma center in neighbouring Toronto.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] Another pilot, the West Rouge Automated Shuttle program, was announced in spring 2021 by the Toronto Transit Commission from Rouge Hill GO Station, but the service was never started after the demise of Local Motors in 2022.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] Local Motors had microfactories in Phoenix, Knoxville, Las Vegas, Louisville, and Washington, DC.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] In February 2017, Local Motors closed its Las Vegas location.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/local-motors] Local Motors closed on 14 January 2022, with their closure announced by Chris Stoner, their former VP of sales and customer success.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/lubrication] Adequate lubrication allows smooth, continuous operation of machine elements, reduces the rate of wear, and prevents excessive stresses or seizures at bearings.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/lubrication] By repelling water and other substances, it also reduces corrosion.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/lubrication] When lubrication breaks down, components can rub destructively against each other, causing heat, local welding, destructive damage and failure.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/lubrication] Besides supporting the load the lubricant may have to perform other functions as well, for instance it may cool the contact areas and remove wear products.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/lubrication] While carrying out these functions the lubricant is constantly replaced from the contact areas either by the relative movement (hydrodynamics) or by externally induced forces.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/lubrication] Lubrication is required for correct operation of mechanical systems such as pistons, pumps, cams, bearings, turbines, gears, roller chains, and cutting tools.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/lubrication] Without lubrication, the pressure between the surfaces in proximity would generate enough heat for rapid surface damage which, in a coarsened condition, could literally weld the surfaces together, causing seizure.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/lubrication] In some applications, such as piston engines, the film between the piston and the cylinder wall also seals the combustion chamber, preventing combustion gases from escaping into the crankcase.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/lubrication] If an engine required pressurised lubrication to, say, plain bearings, there would be an oil pump and an oil filter.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/lubrication] On early engines (such as a Sabb marine diesel), where pressurised feed was not required splash lubrication would suffice.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] The initiative began as a result of lectures given by David Edstrom of Sun Microsystems and David Patterson, professor of Computer Science at the University of California, Berkeley (UCB) at the 2006 annual meeting of the Association for Manufacturing Technology (AMT).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] The two lectures promoted an open communication standard to enable Internet connectivity to manufacturing equipment.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] The resulting standard is available under royalty-free licensing terms.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] MTConnect is a protocol designed for the exchange of data between shop floor equipment and software applications used for monitoring and data analysis.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] MTConnect is referred to as a read-only standard, meaning that it only defines the extraction (reading) of data from control devices, not the writing of data to a control device.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] Freely available, open standards are used for all aspects of MTConnect.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] Data from shop floor devices is presented in XML format, and is retrieved from information providers, called Agents, using Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) as the underlying transport protocol.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] MTConnect provides a RESTful interface, which means the interface is stateless.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] No session must be established to retrieve data from an MTConnect Agent, and no logon or logoff sequence is required (unless overlying security protocols are added which do).
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) is recommended for discovery services.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] Version 1.0 was released in December 2008.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] The first public demonstration of MTConnect occurred at the International Manufacturing Technology Show (IMTS) held in Chicago, Illinois September 2008.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] There, 25 industrial equipment manufacturers networked their machinery control systems, providing process information that could be retrieved from any web-enabled client connected to the network.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] Subsequent demonstrations occurred at EMO (the European machine tool show) in Milan, Italy in October 2009, and the 2010 IMTS in Chicago.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] The MTConnect standard has three sections.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] The first section provides information on the protocol and structure of the XML documents via XML schemas.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] The second section specifies the machine tool components and the description of the available data.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] The third and last section specifies the organization of the data streams that can be provided from a manufacturing device.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] The MTConnect Institute is considering adding a fourth section to support mobile assets that include tools and work-holdings.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] MTConnect took an incremental approach to defining the requirements for manufacturing device communications.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] It did not exhaustively define every possible piece of data an application can collect from a manufacturing device, but it works forward from business and research objectives to define the required elements to meet those needs.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] The standard catalogued important components and data items for metal cutting devices.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] MTConnect provides an extensible XML schema to allow implementors to add custom data to meet their specific needs, while providing as much commonality as possible.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] On September 16, 2010, The MTConnect Institute and the OPC Foundation announced cooperation between the respective organizations.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] The maintenance cost and losses in productivity with unplanned downtime for machine tool components such as spindle bearings and ball screws could be reduced if one could proactively take action prior to failure.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] In addition, cutting tools and inserts are expensive to replace when they are still in good condition, but replacing the tools too late can be costly due to scrap and re-work.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] The proposed health monitoring application will use MTConnect to extract controller data and pattern recognition algorithms to assess the health condition of the spindle and machine tool axes.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] The health assessment approach is based on running a routine program each shift in which the most recent data patterns are compared to the baseline data patterns.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] An online tool condition monitoring module is also proposed and uses controller data such as the spindle motor current, with other add on sensors (vibration, acoustic emission) to accurately estimate and predict tool wear.
[src:international-manufacturing-technology-show/mtconnect] With the added transparency of the machine tool health information, one can take proactive actions before significant downtime or productivity losses occur.
